<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hope </PERSON> wants to send country singer <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> `` to <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> with love,'' and played host of a fund-raising dinner in pursuit of that goal. At Friday's dinner, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said he was eager to return to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on his second goodwill tour. `` I guess I was the first person to introduce country music to the Russians, and they loved it,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said. `` I, in turn, loved them. They're just people, not so different from us.'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said work songs like `` Sixteen Tons'' were the most-requested tunes when he first toured the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1976. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, who stars on the television show `` <PERSON> Hee </PERSON> <PERSON> Haw </PERSON>,'' will give 12 concerts in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> on this tour, which is partially funded by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and the official Soviet talent agency Gosconcert. Tennessee Sens. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON> joined <PERSON> Hee </PERSON> <PERSON> Haw </PERSON> co-star <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindsey </PERSON> at the fund-raiser, which included some light jabs at Clark by <PERSON> Hope </PERSON>. `` I send him to <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>, with love,'' <PERSON> Hope </PERSON> said. `` It's either send him, or deport him. Who else would want him, except maybe his wife?''
