<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE WITH Gilbert upgraded to
hurricane. Picks up 7th graf pvs `Two weeks...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tropical Storm <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> strengthened into a hurricane Saturday night in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, boasting maximum sustained winds of nearly 75 mph, forecasters said. <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> was expected drop 5 to 10 inches of rain on <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> by Sunday, the National Hurricane Center said. At 10:30 p.m. EDT Saturday, <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> was centered 225 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Santo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Domingo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>. It was near latitude 16.0 north, longitude 67.3 west. Forecasters expected the storm to continue to strengthen. `` The system is becoming better organized,'' said <PERSON> Lixion </PERSON> <PERSON> Avila </PERSON>, hurricane center meteorologist. `` The convection is becoming concentrated in the center.'' The storm was expected to continue moving west at near 15 mph for the next 24 hours. The government of the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> issued a hurricane warning for the <PERSON> Barahona </PERSON> peninsula. Two weeks ago, a depression that later became Tropical Storm <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> dumped 6.6 inches of rain on <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, causing mudslides and flooding blamed for three deaths and damage to more than 100 homes. <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> came ashore Aug. 28 at <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, destroying more than a dozen mobile homes, killing one person, and leaving thousands temporarily without power before losing steam over land. Meanwhile, the remnants of hurricane <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> moved into <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> on Saturday while thousands of evacuated <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> residents returned to their homes. Most found little damage from the storm's 80 mph wind. Officials blamed <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> for one death. The 1988 <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> hurricane season has had eight named storms, two of which strengthened into short-lived hurricanes.
