<HEAD>At Least Two Large Animals Confirmed Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COOKE CITY, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A black bear and a mule deer buck are the first large animals confirmed killed by the forest fires in and near <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, and firefighters have been warned to avoid any injured animals. Yellowstone National Park officials had repeatedly said that larger animals such as deer, elk, bison and bear can easily sidestep fires that advance normally. However, fires in the <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> area have not behaved normally. Veteran firefighters in and around the park say they have never seen fire move so far, so quickly. The black bear was suffering from deep burns on its feet and was unable to do more than lift its head Friday evening, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Safford </PERSON>, a highway patrolman who was given permission by state and local officials to shoot and kill the suffering animal about a half mile east of Silver Gate. `` All four pads were burned off the feet and down to the bone. He must have run through a bunch of hot coals. It looked to me like he would have been permanently immobile,'' <PERSON> Safford </PERSON> said. The bear, about 4 years old, had been seen lying in a marsh about 200 yards above a highway for about 24 hours before it was killed. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Folenius </PERSON>, safety officer on the Storm Creek fire, told firefighters at Saturday's 6 a.m. briefing that there had been sightings of some hurt bears and cautioned firefighters to be careful around them if they were spotted. About seven miles west of where the bear was killed, the charred carcass of a mature buck deer lay beside the road to <LOCATION> Daisy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pass </LOCATION>. Fire scoured the area Wednesday. Another carcass was reported to be nearby, but could not be located.
