<FIRST>r w PM-PostalCutbacks Bjt   09-10 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Postal Cutbacks, Bjt,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Postal Window Service Restored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Postal Service today is restoring the window services it cut last February in a move that saved $ 40 million and helped cushion an expected $ 500 million deficit this year for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mail system. Hours at post offices wo n't necessarily be the same as before the cuts were imposed, however, with local managers allowed to make changes that they think best serve their customers. Ordered by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to cut out $ 160 million in spending, the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> made a series of changes, including reducing window hours at most offices by a half-day per week. The reduction in hours drew heavy criticism, coming just two months before postage rates were increased. Postmaster General <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> has struggled to explain that the two events were not related. The rate increase was in response to a rising deficit, and had been in the works for more than a year. The service cuts were necessitated when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> unexpectedly ordered the spending reduction. It was part of an effort to reduce the overall federal budget, even though the post office no longer receives a taxpayer subsidy. In restoring the window hours, local managers were given the option to adjust hours to suit the needs of their communities. For example, Saturday hours will not be restored in heavily Jewish sections of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, where little business was done on that day anyway because of the sabbath. Instead, managers will experiment with staying open later some days or perhaps having some Sunday office hours. In other areas, instead of extending hours overall, managers will add more clerks to handle business during peak times. While the hours of window clerk service are returning, other money-saving cuts imposed in February remain in effect, including curtailment of Sunday mail collection and sorting and a moratorium on construction of new post offices. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, is considering bills to remove the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> from the federal budget as a way to avoid similar service reductions in the future. The window closings saved about $ 40 million, officials reported. Unless action is taken, the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> faces another $ 270 million in spending cuts in the fiscal year that starts Oct. 1. That will not mean that hours will be cut again, however. Postal managers say they have found ways to cut spending _ although at the cost of slower service _ by such things as switching some mail from airplanes to trucks, changing trucking schedules, reducing management travel and training spending and cutting research and development. The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> expects to finish the current fiscal year at the end of this month with a deficit of between $ 500 million and $ 550 million. Higher postage rates which took effect April 4 are expected to help boost the agency into the black in fiscal 1989, however. The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has managed to break even over the last decade, losing money in some years and showing a surplus in others.
</TEXT>
