<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The High Court sentenced a 78-year-old scavenger to death by hanging after convicting him of possessing 6.4 pounds of opium. <PERSON> Teng </PERSON> <PERSON> Soi </PERSON> told the court he had just picked up the bag containing the opium at a dump when he was arrested Nov. 24, 1984. He said he did not know what was in the bag. Justice K.C. <PERSON> Vohrah </PERSON>, in passing the death sentence, said it was improbable anyone would throw into the garbage that amount of cocaine. <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> in 1975 passed laws providing the death penalty for drug trafficking. Since then, 184 people have been sentenced to death and 62 have been executed by hanging. The others are awaiting appeals or execution dates.
