<SECOND>PM-Medicaid Abortions,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Effort To Amend Medicaid Abortion Rules Seems Doomed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first attempt to liberalize Medicaid abortion restrictions in seven years appears doomed to failure in the wake of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote to continue paying for abortions only when a woman's life is endangered. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted 216-166 Friday to stand by existing policy rather than go along with a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan to permit government-financed abortions for poor victims of rape and incest. The abortion controversy arose in connection with a $ 140 billion spending bill for the departments of labor, education and health and human services that also included funds for AIDS and student financial aid. House and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators came to agreement on every other element of the massive fiscal 1989 appropriations bill, but were stymied on abortion. The House action added to mounting pressure on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to back off its amendment. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has said repeatedly he would veto the entire spending bill if abortion policy is liberalized. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> could act on the bill and the abortion question as early as Monday, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, indicated `` We are disappointed but not defeated,'' said <PERSON> Kate </PERSON> <PERSON> Michelman </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abortion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, in a statement after the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote. Apparently anticipating a similar setback in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, she added, `` we shall redouble our efforts with the new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the new administration and we'll try again.'' Under an amendment authored by Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., Medicaid pays only for abortions needed to save the life of a woman It had been seven years since either chamber had voted to liberalize the policy until the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> adopted the rape and incest provision on July 27. Specifically, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> measure said Medicaid would pay for abortions in cases of promptly reported rape or incest. States still would have the option of barring payments for all abortions except those necessary to save a woman's life. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, legislative director for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right-to-Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, issued a statement saying `` the groups pushing for these changes really want to restore federal funding of abortion on demand.'' Much of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> debate centered on the fundamental morality of abortion, despite the narrow focus of the amendment. `` You ca n't avoid injustice in a rape situation. You ca n't avoid injustice in an incest situation. But why compound the injustice by putting on top of it exterminating an innocent human life?'' <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON> said. `` Do n't make us a part of that double tragedy. ... Out of great, great tragedy, some good can come.'' Lawmakers on the other side argued with equal passion that poor women victimized by brutal crimes are entitled to a full range of medical options. `` The consequences to individuals are very substantial,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Steny </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyer </PERSON>, D-Md. `` This is the appropriate and sensitive and humane step for us to take.'' <PERSON> Faye </PERSON> <PERSON> Wattleton </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Planned </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parenthood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, accused the House of treating poor women callously. `` To force a woman to bear her rapist's child because she is poor is the cruelest insult imaginable,'' <PERSON> Wattleton </PERSON> said in a statement. However, some <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON> allies noted that medical procedures are available to prevent conception after rapes or incest. Others said the proposed exceptions would create problems for law enforcement officers confronted with reports of rape. `` What we're going to do is make liars out of women so that they can get an abortion funded by the government,'' contended Rep. <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Volkmer </PERSON>, D-Mo. Before moving to the abortion debate, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted 335-60 to approve the other portions of the three-agency spending bill. The measure includes $ 1.2 billion for AIDS research, treatment, prevention and education; $ 4.3 billion in education grants for disadvantaged students; $ 5.5 billion in college student financial assistance, and $ 3.7 billion for the Job Training Partnership Act.
</TEXT>
