<HEAD>Serbia Leader's Defiance Sparks National Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First available for Saturday AMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Serbian <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief's public defiance of the national leadership has thrown this <LOCATION> Balkan </LOCATION> country of competing ethnic groups into its most explosive political crisis of the postwar era <PERSON> Slobodan </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> on Tuesday rejected a call from the federal <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presidium </ORGANIZATION> to put an end to nationalist rallies in the southern province of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, where minority Slavs contend they are harrassed by ethnic Albanians who form 90 percent of the province's population. On Tuesday, more than 100,000 Serbs and Montenegrins, who are Slavs, staged protest rallies. Demonstrators shouted, `` Give us arms'' and `` Army to <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>,'' underscoring the Serbian leadership's demand to send the army to <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> to restore order. <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> is an autonomous region within the republic of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> and other Serbian leaders want to change the federal constitution so the republic can assert control over <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> and the autonomous province of <LOCATION> Vojvodina </LOCATION>. Under the 1974 constitution, <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> can not interfere in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>'s judiciary, police or other institutions Leaders of other republics oppose the idea. Newspaper editorials have said that the foundation of the Yugoslav state is threatened. Commenting on the showdown, the daily Vjesnik of <LOCATION> Zagreb </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Croatia </LOCATION>, warned that an increasing number of Yugoslavs were questioning the 1943 agreement that gave birth to communist <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. The nation is made up of six republics, each of which has its own constitution, assembly and president. `` We witness a sharpening of nationalism and chauvinism on the entire <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> territory,'' the editorial said. <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>'s supporters planned weekend rallies in the city of <LOCATION> Jajce </LOCATION>, where the agreement was worked out, but local officials rejected the plan. The organizers then said they would hold a `` solidarity meeting'' there Sept. 17. <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> has lashed out at the national leadership by saying the <LOCATION> Serbs </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Montenegrins </ORGANIZATION> have `` shown patience for the inefficiency of this country and the incompetence of its representatives.'' In Tuesday's speech, he asserted <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> leaders failed to bring peace to <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>. Referring to Slavs living there, he said, `` This summer their patience came to an end.'' <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> defended the fast-spreading Serbian discontent as justified expression of popular sentiment, while opponents say it will result in anarchy. Within hours, the <ORGANIZATION> Yugoslav </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> scheduled a session for late September to take action on <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON>, who enjoys popular support in <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> press. On Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency said a police unit from another part of <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION> would leave for <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> to reinforce local police. On Thursday, more than 10,000 Serbs and Montenegrins assembled at the <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Vucitrn </LOCATION> to protest what they called `` aggressive assaults of Albanian chauvinists and separatists,'' the <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Politika </ORGANIZATION> reported. The rally followed an attack last week on the home of a Serbian woman. Two ethnic Albanians, convicted of damaging the house, were sentenced to 30 days in jail. The ethnic <PERSON> Albanian </PERSON> judge involved was dismissed and the terms were increased to 60 days. Demonstrators were heard singing a folk song that boldly compares <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> to the late President <PERSON> Josip </PERSON> <PERSON> Broz </PERSON> <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>, the virtually uncontested leader of non-aligned <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> for three decades. Most Belgrade newspapers give a lopsided view of what is going on in <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, scene of bloody rioting for greater autonomy in 1981. They keep reiterating that more than 30,000 Serbs and <PERSON> Montenegrins </PERSON> left the province in recent years because of arson and other attacks blamed on Albanians. Ethnic Albanians are rarely given a chance to respond in public to what appear to be grossly distorted accounts. In the regime-controlled press, the Slav exodus is entirely blamed on the Albanians, an estimated 500 of whom are in jail. The <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported Friday that authorities in <LOCATION> Duesseldorf </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, warned Albanian families from towns in <LOCATION> Macedonia </LOCATION> they would be turned down as political refugees because `` their true motives ... are purely economic.'' Conversely, <LOCATION> Serbian </LOCATION> media have had practically no reports that Slavs have relocated for economic reasons from <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s most underdeveloped region
</TEXT>
