<HEAD>Union, Police Blame Each Other for Violence; 13th Strike Set for
Monday</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BAI4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police fired rubber bullets and water cannons to break up an anti-government rally of 20,000 during a nationwide general strike. Labor leaders called for another work stoppage Monday. The clashes with police, vandalism, burning of cars and looting of stores resulted in dozens of injuries and arrests during the walkout Friday protesting spiraling inflation and unemployment. The unrest made the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conferation </ORGANIZATION>'s 12th general strike against the nearly 5-year-old government of President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> the most disorderly and bloody. Labor leaders and police blamed each other for the violence. `` It's a lie that the incidents began among participants of the rally,'' said <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> Ubaldini </PERSON>, general-secretary of the labor confederation. Interior Minister <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Nosiglia </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Pirker </PERSON> said agitators in the crowd started fights, as did members of rival unions. When police attempted to restore order, they were attacked, the said. `` Under these circumstances, police intervened to prevent further damage,'' <PERSON> Nosiglia </PERSON> said. The police action was `` necessary, prudent and correct,'' <PERSON> Pirker </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Nosiglia </PERSON> in a brief communique urged the federation to call off the Monday walkout. `` Nothing justifies a new paralysis of the country, which keeps delaying progress without any benefit to rights and liberties,'' he said. No deaths were reported in the unrest Friday, but several people had not regained consciousness hours after they were hospitalized. About 50 people were treated at <LOCATION> Argerich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> for tear gas inhalation, contusions from rocks and sticks, and abrasions from falling to the ground when struck by compressed water fired by riot police. Several dozen others went to at least two other hospitals. Two policemen were rushed to <LOCATION> Churruca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> with severe injuries, and about 20 others were treated for minor injuries. <PERSON> Pirker </PERSON> said he did not know the total number of people arrested. Inflation has soared 255 percent this year, and 440 percent for the past 12 months. Unemployment and underemployment at a combined 14 percent are near 14-year highs. Real personal incomes have declined for three straight years. `` Every day there's less work and my family ca n't live on what I earn,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rio </PERSON>, a middle-aged truck driver who attended the rally. `` That's why I'm here.'' President <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> five weeks ago implemented his third major anti-inflation plan since he took office in December 1983. The austral was devalued, restrictions on some imports were lifted and voluntary controls placed on wages and prices. The goal, in addition to reducing inflation, was to secure new loans from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> and commercial banks to help repay interest _ $ 4.6 billion this year _ on <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s $ 56 billion foreign debt. Unions and the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> raise the sensitive issue of national sovereignty in response to <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s shaping of national policy to meet demands by foreign banks. The 3.5-million member federation has complained bitterly that prices have risen despite the controls and pressed for higher wages. Friday's strike was effective across this South American country of 30 million. In the capital, <PERSON> Buenos </PERSON> <PERSON> Aires </PERSON>, striking signalmen shut down commuter trains before dawn, stranding thousands of people at home and causing huge backups on roads leading downtown. After 8 p.m., the hour the strike was scheduled to end, public transportation resumed and the capital city of 3 million was calm. Late Friday, several public transport unions said they would participate in Monday's strike, indicating that buses and subways will be out of service as well as commuter trains.
