<HEAD>Democrats Concede They Lack Votes to Pass Sanctions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democrats are pressing ahead with a package of economic sanctions against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, but concede that a united front of Republican opposition will probably keep the measure from coming to a vote in the full chamber. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> will vote next Wednesday on the bill, which would impose a near-total trade embargo against white-dominated <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and a near-total withdrawal of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investment in the country. Republican members of the panel, accusing Democrats of playing election-year politics with the issue, refused a chance to offer amendments to the bill on Friday. They said they prefer the bill as it stands because it is so extensive that it will not attract enough votes to cut off a filibuster on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor. `` My guess is that it will be approved by the committee,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., a principal author of the legislation `` But because the Republicans are apparently united it will not have the votes to overcome a filibuster _ we wo n't get cloture _ that's the way it looks right now,'' said <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>. `` But even if we do nothing more than pass it out of committee, it is a signal to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> that we want to change the system'' of forced racial separation known as apartheid, he said. Sixty votes are required in the 100-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to invoke cloture and cut off debate on a bill. The 1988 Democratic platform brands <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> a terrorist state and Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has supported sanctions. Republican presidential candidate <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has opposed new sanctions on they ground they would remove any leverage the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> may have to work for change in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. After a morning-long debate on the sanctions bill, <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> committee member Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, told reporters: `` I think it's clearly, clearly pushed by domestic political considerations and not be the urgency of the situation in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. I think the bill as it now sits will not have a single Republican vote on the committee.'' A coalition of Democrats and Republicans enacted a milder South African sanctions bill two years ago over President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto. Supporters of the present measure contend it is needed because the earlier and less-sweeping bill has not forced the South African government to end apartheid and to extend full citizenship rights to the black majority. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> adopted a similar version of the far-reaching <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill on Aug. 11.
