<HEAD>Festival Lost In The Controversy Over Scorsese Film</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sixty films were presented at this year's <ORGANIZATION> Venice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION>, but it was <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON>'s `` The Last Tempatation of Christ'' that monopolized attention, frustrating directors who feared their work was lost in the controversy Even before the festival began, the Italian media had dubbed it `` The Festival of Controversy'' because of protests against <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON>'s film. It includes a sequence in which <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> hallucinates on the cross about abandoning his role as savior, marrying <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Magdalene </PERSON> and raising a family. <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON>'s film already had been under heavy attack in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and elsewhere from some Christians and church groups. In <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>, the film was condemned by <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops, <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>, followers of excommunicated Archbishop <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lefebvre </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s dominant Christian Democrat party. `` The importance of Scorsese comes from the fact that it was the first screening in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and people were interested in seeing the reaction in a society very different from <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> ... in the center of the Catholic world,'' said <PERSON> Adriano </PERSON> <PERSON> Donaggio </PERSON>, spokesman for the festival that ended Friday. Festival director <PERSON> Guglielmo </PERSON> <PERSON> Biraghi </PERSON>, a former critic, said he welcomed the controversy as long as it was constructive. But some directors feared their work would simply vanish in the fog surrounding Scorsese and his film. Italian director <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeffirelli </PERSON> once threatened to withdraw his film, `` Il Giovane Toscanini'' -LRB- The Young <PERSON> Toscanini </PERSON> -RRB-, because he feared it could be overlooked if shown too close to <ORGANIZATION> Scorsese </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>. In the end, <PERSON> Zeffirelli </PERSON> left <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> in a huff, vowing never to return. His film drew sustained applause from the <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> audience but painful reviews from the critics. `` I have brought my film to <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> to satisfy the producers. I did not want to come. Now I put on my crown of thorns and here I am, on <LOCATION> Calvary </LOCATION>,'' he said at a news conference Monday. In a telling incident, <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> director <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Almodovar </PERSON> angrily returned to a news conference Wednesday moments after he left to berate festival officials for excluding some <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> journalists. But actually, it was the police who denied entry to the late-arriving Spaniards. They feared the conference room already was dangerously overcrowded. Hundreds were waiting for <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON>, who was greeted with an ovation when he arrived surrounded by bodyguards. During the turbulent news conference, <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON> defended his film as a work of fiction, based on a novel. He said the film did not seek to change anyone's religious convictions. The film was panned by many critics in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, who complained of uninspired acting and banal dialouge. Still, <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON> was seen by many as a symbol of standing against censorship. `` The biggest problem at this festival was Scorsese,'' said <PERSON> Donaggio </PERSON>. But he added that the Scorsese film was also one of the festival's successes this year. The success, he said, was defending the right to show a controversial film and let the public be the judge.
