<HEAD>Firefighters Weary, But Have A Job To Do</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SILVER GATE, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After a month battling fires, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gearhart </PERSON> would like nothing more than a break. But he does n't expect one as the worst fires in <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>'s history burn `` We're real tired, that's for sure,'' <PERSON> Gearhart </PERSON> said Friday while on the fire line near the tiny community of Silver Gate, which has been under seige by blazes for a week. `` We could still go on, but we've been away a long time,'' he said. `` We'd like to go home for just a few days, and then they could bring us back.'' <PERSON> Gearhart </PERSON>, a member of the Vista Grande Hot Shots from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernadino </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, has been on the line 35 days. Normally firefighters are released for several days after 21 days. But these are not normal times. More than 800,000 acres in nearby <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> have burned. The 151,000-acre Storm Creek-Hellroaring fire, one of several in and around the park, persists in threatening Silver Gate and <LOCATION> Cooke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> northeast of the park. Firefighters see no sign of an improvement, with high winds forecast over the weekend that are expected to fan the flames. `` We are anticipating major fire activity,'' forest service official <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Avery </PERSON> said, adding that today `` may be the worst day since this entire episode began.'' Today was to have been the day <PERSON> Gearhart </PERSON> got a day off. But then, so was Friday _ until Friday came. `` Now that this is a national emergency, maybe they'll keep us even longer,'' he said. As a `` hot shot'' <PERSON> Gearhart </PERSON> and his fellow crew members are the first on the lines of the most dangerous sections of fire. He works 12-16 hours a day wielding a chain saw with a blade roughly 4 feet long, and sometim