<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Radical students yelling `` Oppose dictatorial Olympics!'' hurled hundreds of firebombs at riot police today. Student leaders charged the Games were being used to cement military rule. About 2,000 students from several <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> colleges rallied at the capital's <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, denouncing the Olympics, President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>'s government and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for backing the government. `` Down with military dictatorship,'' the students chanted as they marched around the campus with red, white and blue flags. The students, some armed with wooden and iron clubs, then marched out of the school to confront hundreds of riot police who were surrounding the campus. Protesters taunted the police and then attacked. Waves of masked students rushed out of the school's gates and climbed over walls to pelt police with firebombs that exploded in orange balls of blazing gasoline. The firebombs exploded among the police, setting fire to troopers' shields and clothing. Police, dressed in green combat fatigues and black visored helmets, did not use tear gas because of government orders not to use the powerful gas during the Olympics. They also hurled back fewer rocks than in similar protests in the past. Police said they had no reports of arrests or injuries. The clash lasted about 30 minutes and was confined to the highway in front of the school. Student and dissident leaders speaking at the rally charged the <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> government with using the Olympics, which begin Sept. 17, to cement authoritarian rule. `` The Olympics are being used to cement the fascist regime,'' said a statement by the protesters. `` The regime is making all out efforts to weaken the people's power.'' Speakers charged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with conspiring with <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> to continue military rule. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has about 42,000 troops in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> under a mutual defense pact. Radical leaders have called for anti-Olympic protests, but the protests so far have been confined to a few campuses in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and several other cities. There have been no demonstrations near Olympic sites. The radicals, a small but powerful minority on campuses, have virtually no public support. Most Koreans are critical of protests against the Olympics and want nothing to disrupt the Games. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>, a former general who won presidential elections in December, has introduced broad democratic reforms and dismantled authoritarian controls.
