<HEAD>Evacuees Wax Philosophical About Florence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Florence, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALBERTO S. FRANCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELLE CHASSE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Encalade </PERSON> was philosophical about <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION>, the hurricane that chased him from his home exactly 23 years after an equally rude uprooting at the hands of Hurricane Betsy. As he sat among 1,200 other evacuees at <ORGANIZATION> Belle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chasse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> just south of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> on Friday night, the 69-year-old <PERSON> Encalade </PERSON> said living through storms is a way of life. `` People live all their lives down here,'' he said. `` You hate to leave. You go somewhere else and a tornado will take you or something else will. `` It's discouraging, but what are you going to do?'' he said. `` If you're too old, you ca n't go far.'' <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> was at hurricane strength Friday when the evacuees left their low-lying homes, but lost its punch as it brushed the coast and was downgraded to a tropical storm this morning. Thousands of residents of coastal areas in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> also took refuge in shelters and homes of relatives and friends on higher ground. Despite an almost casual acceptance of his situation, <PERSON> Encalade </PERSON> said previous storms have cost him dearly. `` When <PERSON> Camille </PERSON> -LRB- in 1969 -RRB- and <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> came over, they cleaned us out. I lost two houses,'' he said. Now Encalade lives in a trailer in <LOCATION> Buras </LOCATION> on the tip of the <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>. `` We've got it anchored,'' he said. `` But if the storm passes over it's going to take it anyway. So you just lock it up and come up here and see what happens.'' At the school, cots were set up in the gym, with large families grouped in classrooms. Some people brought TV sets and suitcases with changes of clothes. Sitting on cots, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Melodia </PERSON> <PERSON> Buras </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Boothville </LOCATION> were a little more pragmatic than Encalade. `` I've been in this school three times already,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Buras </PERSON> said. `` Once for <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> and once for <PERSON> Camille </PERSON>. When it's a hurricane, I'm gone.'' They said they normally ride out weaker storms at home, but anytime a hurricane nears shore they head for higher ground. Mrs. <PERSON> Buras </PERSON> said her quick departures when bad weather threatens sometimes draw jokes from neighbors. `` They laugh at us when we get back, but I'd rather be safe.'' Many shared the same outlook at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bernard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> east of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, where 170 evacuees took refuge. `` Where we live is ` God's Little Acre,''' said <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzales </PERSON>, 65, of <LOCATION> Delcroix </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. `` It's the best place to live even though every time a storm comes through, we've got to go.'' So why not move? `` If our home's destroyed, we'll make another government loan and build again,'' she said.
</TEXT>
