<SECOND>PM-Redistricting Suit,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hispanic Leaders See Change in New Political Map For L.A. County</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0481 to restore logo.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A lawsuit that seeks to redress alleged discrimination against <PERSON> Hispanics </PERSON> will represent a fundamental reordering of political priorities in the nation's most populous county, Hispanic leaders say. The suit, filed this week by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, alleges that county officials discriminated against Hispanics by drawing political boundaries so as to dilute the influence of Hispanic voters. `` It should have happened years ago,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, 55, president of a thriving grocery business who was the first Mexican-American to serve on the city's <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commissioners </ORGANIZATION>. `` I'm just so excited about it.'' <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> predicted that changing the electoral districts would lead to higher voter turnout because of the likelihood that Hispanic candidates will run for the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervisors </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> and others said they expect redistricting will result in changes in county government services, particularly in health care, zoning, police protection and social services. A similar <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> case against the city government in 1985 resulted in redrawn boundaries in which Hispanics comprise a majority in at least three of the city's 15 council districts. Hispanic leaders say far more is at stake in the county redistricting case. For one thing, no Hispanic or any other minority group member has ever been elected to the county Board of Supervisors. Yet the percentage of Hispanics in the county is at least 27 percent, with blacks comprising more than 12 percent and Asians about 5.8 percent, according to the lawsuit. `` Without a doubt, at least in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervisors </ORGANIZATION> is one of the most powerful elected bodies in government,'' said City Councilman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Alatorre </PERSON>. `` Being elected to the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervisors </ORGANIZATION> is like being elected pope,'' <PERSON> Alatorre </PERSON> said. `` They're the five gods.'' `` I call them the five kings, and a lot of people call them the five kings because of their imperial manner,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON>, a state civil rights representative for the <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Latin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION>. Such an appraisal is due in large part to the sheer size of county government. The Board of Supervisors controls a budget of nearly $ 9 billion, compared to the city's budget of roughly $ 3.5 billion. The county's population, estimated at 8.5 million, is greater than that in each of 42 states. Roughly translated, that means that each of the five supervisors has a constituency of 1.6 million to 1.7 million people. In comparison, the ideal population set for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Congressional Districts during the reapportionment of the early 1980s was a mere 526,000. And at 2,615 square miles, the county's 5th District seat in northern <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> is bigger than the state of <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>. Such huge numbers, <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> said, means that immense power is concentrated in the hands of a very few. Conversely, <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> added, mounting a political challenge against an incumbent supervisor requires tremendous financial resources. Striking a conciliatory tone, <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervisors </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Deane </PERSON> <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> said the suit has left the five-member board with little choice `` except to redraw our lines.'' Hispanic community leaders sounded ecstatic about the prospects of change to be wrought by the voting rights case. `` Hispanic groups have experienced a ` tough guy' kind of attitude from the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supervisors </ORGANIZATION> when they protested over clinics that have been closed,'' said City Councilwoman <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Molina </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s intervention, <PERSON> Ms. </PERSON> <PERSON> Molina </PERSON> said, is `` sending a tremendously positive message to a Hispanic community that felt they had no place to go in terms of political redress.'' <PERSON> Ms. </PERSON> <PERSON> Molina </PERSON>, who was elected to represent east <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> in February 1987, was one of the first politicians to benefit from the city's redistricting case, and she believes that she has brought important changes to the council. `` Having a Hispanic on the City Council has created kind of an attitude change,'' <PERSON> Ms. </PERSON> <PERSON> Molina </PERSON> said. `` Before, there were many issues that were not addressed.''
</TEXT>
