<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo and civic activist <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beard </PERSON> faced off in a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> primary today to determine who will try to unseat Republican <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>. Voter turnout was critical in today's race, the only statewide competition in the primary. Volunteers from both camps planned to canvass door-to-door and by telephone, as well as provide transportation to the polls. A light turnout was expected to favor <PERSON> Beard </PERSON>, who was backed by unions and party regulars who traditionally go to the polls in force. A heavy turnout was considered good for Woo, whose main support comes from college students and younger groups. Polls opened at 7 a.m. and were to close at 8 p.m. `` We're making sure we're real well-organized and getting our people out,'' Woo's deputy campaign manager, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Markell </PERSON>, said Friday. A poll conducted late last month for the <ORGANIZATION> Wilmington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Journal </ORGANIZATION> newspapers gave Woo 45 percent of the vote and Beard 31 percent. Twenty-four percent of the likely voters polled were undecided. Woo, a 51-year-old physics professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION>, was elected lieutenant governor four years ago in his first bid for public office. A native of <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, he became a symbol of success by Asian-Americans. Woo was considered a shoo-in for another term as lieutenant governor, but instead chose to challenge <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, who is seeking his fourth term. However, Democrats complained <PERSON> Woo </PERSON> is not loyal to the party and threw their support behind Beard. Beard, 49, is a former staffer of the late Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N </LOCATION>. He owns a non-profit company that helps obtain grants to attract economic devleopment. Woo apparently won the battle for campaign donations. By late August, he had raised $ 407,998, with most of the money from the Asian-American community. Beard raised $ 65,008. <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, who runs unopposed in the primary, had $ 734,933.
