 Tropical storm <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION> whipped the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> with severe winds today and spread rain as far north as southern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. The storm's strength diminished, and it was downgraded from hurricane status as it passed by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> and headed for <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. Hurricane warnings had been posted from near <LOCATION> Morgan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, through to <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and tropical storm warnings for winds to 50 mph were posted from <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Apalachicola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. Tides were expected to run as much as 9 feet above normal and between 5 and 10 inches of rain was likely in areas covered by the hurricane warning The Naval Air Station near <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> recorded just under 2 -LCB- inches of rain in the six hours ended at 2 a.m. EDT. The storm system's northern edge cast rain over <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. Most of the rest of the country was dry. Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms across <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> states from <LOCATION> Louisana </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Panhandle </LOCATION> and into <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and eastern <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. Widely scattered showers were expected in central <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and the mountains of <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. Highs were forecast to be in the 60s from the upper <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> to the northern <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> 