<HEAD>Judge Blocks Enforcement of First-in-Nation `Temptation' Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 50 people attended the first showing of the controversial film, `` The Last Temptation of Christ,'' after a federal judge blocked a first-in-the-nation county ordinance banning theaters from showing it. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinson </PERSON> issued a preliminary injunction Friday to stop enforcement of the ordinance, saying it was unconstitutional. <PERSON> Vinson </PERSON> added that `` red flags should run up'' whenever government tries to violate the rights of citizens. The ordinance had called for a maximum penalty of up to a $ 500 fine and 60 days in jail for showing the film. About a dozen pickets were at the Plaza III Theaters for the movie's debut Friday, but there was no violence. In their complaint against the ordinance, the movie's director, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON>, and <ORGANIZATION> Plitt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theaters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> Escambia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> was the first local government to ban the film outright, although others have passed resolutions opposing it. County commissioners passed the ordinance on a 4-1 vote Thursday on the advice of County Attorney <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Buztrey </PERSON>, after <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> fundamentalists and a group called <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pornography </ORGANIZATION> asked for the ban. Opponents objected to the film's humanizing of Christ, particularly a scene in which he has a sexual fantasy involving <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Magdalene </PERSON>. <PERSON> Buztrey </PERSON> argued against the injunction, contending the film was pornographic and patently offensive to the majority of citizens in the county. `` It may be acceptable in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, but it is n't acceptable in <LOCATION> Escambia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>,'' he said. But <PERSON> Vinson </PERSON> listened to a tape recording of the emergency meeting and said he heard no arguments concerning either obscenity or violence. The only argument made by commissioners or citizens who spoke at the meeting was that the film was sacreligious. <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, a lawyer representing the director and theater company, cited rulings by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> that it is not the business of government to suppress real or imagined attacks on a particular religion. <PERSON> Vinson </PERSON> agreed the case was virtually identical to ones in which the high court has disallowed prior restraint of free speech or expression.
