<HEAD>Ortega Proposes New Talks With Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said his government is willing to meet in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> with Contra rebels to discuss resuming high-level peace talks aimed at ending the civil war. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said Friday that Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> would go to <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> `` to discuss with a <LOCATION> Contra </LOCATION> delegation a next meeting in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> and to hear their concerns -LRB- and -RRB- fears are about coming to <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>.'' The president said in a speech that the preliminary talks should take place Sept. 19-20 in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` I would like to have the cable in my hand before I reply. I came from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> yesterday, this is the first news I have,'' Nicaraguan Resistance director <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> said from his home in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> today. A cease-fire in the 7-year-old civil war between the U.S.-backed rebels and the leftist Sandinistas began March 21. But high-level negotiations in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> on a permanent truce broke down on June 9. Contra leaders claimed the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> restricted their freedom of movement in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> and said future talks must be held in another Central American country. The government has extended the cease-fire on a monthly basis, most recently to Sept. 30. The rebels say they will abide by the truce indefinitely, but each side has accused the other of violations. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said he suggested the preliminary talks in conversations with Guatemalan President <PERSON> Vinicio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cerezo </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> also said conditions existed for a new summit of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American 