<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A time bomb exploded in a crowded bazaar of this frontier city today, and a military officer said 17 people were injured. The bomb was attached to a drinking water tank in the city's main shopping area, said an army explosives expert, Maj. <PERSON> Ghulam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussain </PERSON> It went off around 1:15 p.m, shattering windows, damaging two cars and shaking central <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>. The Khyber bazaar is a grimy, cinderblock warren of merchants and a main transit point for buses, taxis and three-wheeled rickshaws. No group claimed responsibility for the blast, but officials have routinely blamed such acts on agents of neighboring <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s communist government. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> supports Moslem guerrillas fighting the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government and an estimated 50,000 Soviet troops who support it. Under a U.N.-sponsored accord, all Soviet troops are to have left <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by Feb. 15.
