<FIRST>r i AM-Burma-Diplomats     09-10 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma-Diplomats,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hard Times Accompany Push For Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Burma, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES W. HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The struggle for democracy in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> is threatening the nation's food supply, causing shortages of gasoline and increasing prices of fruits and vegetables, diplomats said Saturday. Western diplomatic personnel interviewed here said shortages of food and other supplies were widespread in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s capital Even the exclusive <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> store at which diplomats shop has run out of rice, they said. Diplomats are among the only residents who can still tap the virtually exhausted fuel supply. Many Burmese have had to walk up to 15 miles to take part in anti-government demonstrations, they said. The demonstrations prompted the government Saturday to end 26 years of single-party rule and announce that general elections will be held under a multiparty system. Embassies and foreign organizations sent more than 230 dependents and non-essential staffers to <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> Friday on a special <ORGANIZATION> Thai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> flight, leaving about 400 others awaiting evacuation. Diplomats said the evacuees included Americans, Australians, Filipinos, Malaysians, Indonesians, British, Japanese, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION>, Soviets and Thais. Despite widespread looting and increasing violence in the <LOCATION> Burmese </LOCATION> capital, the diplomats insisted they were evacuated strictly as a precautionary measure and said they hope to return soon. `` The diplomatic store is supposed to have rice, but it has not had it for a week or so,'' said one diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity. Diplomatic personnel `` have the same shortages as everyone else. We get fresh food at the markets but in limited supplies. And it has become very expensive. `` We -LRB- diplomats -RRB- are in the happy position of having freezers, and everyone has been gobbling up the food in their freezers because they are afraid the electricity will go off.'' The food shortage has occurred mainly because strikes and a fuel shortage have made it very difficult to get commodities into the capital. But the diplomat said hoarding is also to blame. Indeed, other diplomats have said the military has been hoarding goods in an attempt to starve the people into submission. Another Western diplomat, also speaking anonymously, said a small bag of rice in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> was selling for 600 kyats -LRB- $ 100 -RRB-, `` and the average person makes less than 400 kyats -LRB- $ 67 -RRB- a month. Vegetables and fruit are still around, but the prices have gone up a lot.'' A lack of gasoline has kept most buses from operating, `` so a lot of people have to walk,'' the diplomat said. `` Thousands of people had to walk 15 miles or more to get into town -LRB- for a pro-democracy rally Friday -RRB-,'' she said. `` They passed our -LRB- diplomatic -RRB- compound for more than an hour. Then they had to walk home again. `` You see almost no cars except for -LRB- those owned by -RRB- diplomats,'' she added. The few buses running `` are packed. You see 25 people sitting on the top of them. A lot of people are not going to work because of the transportation problem.'' Both diplomats said the foreign community had no fear of the massive crowds that have rallied in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> almost daily for several weeks to press for an end to one-party rule and an interim government to lead the country to democracy. But the crowds have made it difficult to move about. `` There are a million out walking but they are gentle, good-natured,'' the first diplomat said. `` There are reports that youngsters have been attacked by military intelligence people, but they -LRB- soldiers -RRB- are not interested in foreigners. `` There have been such huge crowds that if you wanted to get from one side of the city to the other you had to wait for an hour and a half'' for the protesters to pass, the diplomat said. `` Then you go one block and they are snaking back again. `` During the day everything is OK. But at night there are a lot of robbers and looters out and it is not safe.''
