<TEXT>
 The law and order minister described Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> on Saturday as a `` tragic and misled person'' who is challenging the government on the orders of revolutionaries. Also Saturday, a newspaper reported that prominent Afrikaner politicians and academics, including the brother of a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister, will meet next month with Soviet policymakers and black nationalist guerrilla leaders. <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>, the law and order minister, said revolutionaries have decided that <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, leader of the Anglican church in southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, should `` create incidents'' to embarrass <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> during the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential campaign and the current visit to the region by Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>, who oversees the national police force, was reacting to <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>'s recent defiance of an emergency regulation forbidding calls for an election boycott. Three times in the past week, <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> has urged blacks and whites to boycott next month's municipal elections, which many blacks view as an entrenchment of segregated, white-controlled political structures. Police are investigating <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>'s statements to determine whether he should be prosecuted. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>, in a speech reported by the state-run <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said `` naive church leaders'' are being misused by the outlawed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement and South African Communist Party. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, out of personal ambition, is playing a key role in a campaign to `` bring the country to its knees.'' The Argus, a <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> daily, said 18 white <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africans </LOCATION> will travel to <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, in late October for a six-day conference. They will meet with officials of the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement and with a <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> delegation that will include at least two deputy directors of the African Institute of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, it said. South African authorities have discouraged contacts with the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The organization is outlawed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and wages a bombing and sabotage campaign to undermine the Afrikaner-dominated government. According to The Argus, the delegation heading to <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION> will include <PERSON> Willem </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>, a former newspaper editor whose brother, <PERSON> Frederik </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Klerk </PERSON>, is minister of education and a possible candidate to succeed President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>. Others in the group reportedly will include <PERSON> Wynand </PERSON> <PERSON> Malan </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> member who heads the small, anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Frederik </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Zyl </PERSON> <P