<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Burma Announces End To One-Party Rule</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Maung Maung speech confirming
earlier Radio Rangoon announcement. TRIMS to tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s ruling party decided today to end 26 years of single-party rule and to hold a general election under a multiparty system. The decision was a victory for opposition leaders and for hundreds of thousands of Burmese who have taken to the streets in sometimes violent demonstrations that have toppled two presidents in three months. Speaking before 968 delegates at a special party congress, the president admitted that major errors were commmitted by the party and said the interests of the people were paramount. `` Power corrupts, and absolute power corrupts absolutely,'' he said in a speech carried by the state-owned Radio <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION>. He pledged a free and fair general election will be held as soon as possible but gave no date. The broadcast announcer said the decision was unanimously adopted by the delegates of the <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> said a party emergency session of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday will make necessary amendments to the constitution to adopt the multiparty system and also to form an independent commission to supervise the elections. He urged government employes, who have left their jobs in sympathy with the pro-democracy movement, to return to their jobs so the government can function. The special party congress was originally scheduled for Monday to decide whether a referendum on one-party rule would be called. Radio <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> said the delegates today decided to scrap the referendum idea and to go ahead with elections under a multiparty system. Today's announcement came one day after former Prime Minister U Nu, toppled in a 1962 military coup, announced the formation of a rival government to take power from <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>. It was not immediately clear how today's development would affect U Nu's plan, which was not supported by all opposition figures. Also Friday, about 500 renegade soldiers joined protesters demanding formation of an interim government and full democracy. It was the first major defection of troops to the opposition. The moves followed weeks of massive, occasionally bloody turmoil in this isolated Southeast Asian nation that left dozens of people dead. Unofficial reports said the death toll could be in the hundreds from street riots that broke out in July. In a letter to embassies on Friday, 82-year-old U Nu called for general elections Oct. 9. He announced a Cabinet with himself as prime minister, former President <PERSON> Mahn </PERSON> <PERSON> Win </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> as president and retired Gen. Tin Oo, a vocal critic of the current authoritarian leadership, as defense minister. However, Tin Oo and two other members of the rival Cabinet _ retired military commanders <LOCATION> Aung </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shwe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saw </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Myint </LOCATION> _ resigned today, and reliable sources said U Nu had not consulted them about his move. The Bar Council of <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> said students and other opposition groups also had not been consulted. The three men also said in a statement that they were resigning from a League for Democracy and Peace that U Nu had formed earlier to oppose the <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>'s government. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>, an opposition figure and daughter of slain independence leader <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON>, told reporters the announcement of a multiparty system was `` a positive step,'' but said it could take up to two years to form parties to contest in general elections. `` Under the present economic and political situation, an interim government will be the best solution. It -LRB- the interim government -RRB- would deal with economic problems and also hold general elections,'' she told reporters. Another opposition leader, retired Gen. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON>, said he doubted `` the prevailing situation will permit holding of general elections under the present government.'' <PERSON> Toru </PERSON> <PERSON> Ohno </PERSON>, a Japanese <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> specialist at <ORGANIZATION> Osaka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` The fact that the ruling party took action two days ahead of its original schedule ... means that <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>'s government can no longer control or suppress protest. I'm glad the party made the compromise in an effort to seek a peaceful and democratic settlement. Ne Win led the 1962 coup that toppled U Nu. Ne Win resigned as head of the ruling party in July, citing in part widespread street protests in March and June. Riots flared when the party chose <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> to succeed Ne Win. <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> is a hardliner widely hated for his brutal suppression of dissidents. The government said 112 people died in anti-government demonstrations, but diplomats estimated hundreds were killed. <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> resigned Aug. 12 after 17 days in power, and <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> was named to replace him. <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> was <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s first civilian leader in 26 years, but protests and nationwide strikes continued as opponents demanded an immediate end to one-party rule.
