<SECOND>AM-Family Tree, Bjt,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Postmaster General Pushes Family Contact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Postmaster General <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> wants to bring <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s generations closer together, and if that brings the Post Office a little extra business he wo n't mind. `` Plant a Family Tree'' is the name of <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>'s plan, in which millions of family history forms will be given out, in hopes that youngsters will write to their grandparents seeking information to fill them out. `` Letters provide an important link between families. Grandparents often meet their grandchildren through an exchange of letters and photographs long before they see each other face-to-face,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said. But it is n't just a business proposition, says <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>. He could generate more business by concentrating on big advertisers and catalog companies. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is part of the fabric of American life. We do more than deliver the mail. We deliver ideas and dreams and help preserve our heritage,'' he says. As part of the family tree program the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has printed millions of folders which discuss family histories on one side and contain a genealogical form on the back to fill in information on parents, grandparents and great-grandparents. The forms will be available, free, in post offices by the first week in October. To get things started, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> invited 27 third graders from <LOCATION> Dale </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, to his <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office on Friday to hear about the project and mail letters to their grandparents _ letters likely to get special treatment, since they were handed directly to the postmaster general. `` It's just finding out about a generation you do n't have much contact with,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said of his hopes for the program. It's children asking: `` Tell me about yourself, gramps Tell me about my parents when they were my age.'' `` What a compliment, to be asked about yourself by grandchildren,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> added, in an interview. Many youngsters will probably telephone for information, of course. But, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> noted nostalgically, `` You do n't tie ribbons around old phone calls in the attic.'' In some countries, generations live together and get to know each other, but that's not often the way in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. As a result children tend not to know their grandparents very well, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> explained to the youngsters. `` We're running out of glue in this country. People are no longer as family oriented. People are no longer as community oriented ... This is a try to bring the family together,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurst </PERSON> of the 30-million member <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Persons </ORGANIZATION> hailed the program as a way of increasing harmony among people from different generations. `` You can be sure our grandmothers and grandfathers will be as excited as can be to help all the grandchildren around the nation fill in the blanks in their family trees,'' <PERSON> Hurst </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> noted that only after becoming an adult do many people realize what they missed if they were not close to grandparents. And by that time it is often too late. In addition to providing a form for starting a family tree the folder includes tips on pursuing a more detailed family background, including suggested sources for genealogical information, such as the Census, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archives </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Genealogical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>.
