<HEAD>Pope's Trip Could Determine Church's Position On Apartheid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with arrival. Pickup 3rd pvs,
``In an...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS REDMONT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Harare </LOCATION> today on the first leg of a pilgrimage to five black-ruled nations bordering racially-troubled <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Before leaving <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> on the 10-day journey, the pontiff said he hopes he can help solve some of white-led <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s problems on a future trip there. His fourth journey to <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and his 39th abroad will be to <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lesotho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Swaziland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> _ all countries less than 20 years old that vehemently oppose <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> but depend on it for economic survival. In an unusual statement Friday, the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> emphasized the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> was not snubbing <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and hoped to visit the country in the future. It said the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s full schedule on this trip made a stop there impossible. The statement appeared directed at reports the pope had ruled out a visit to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, where a white minority rules 26 million blacks. During nearly 10 years at the helm of the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> has strongly denounced apartheid. `` No system of apartheid or separate development will ever be acceptable as a model for the relations between peoples or races,'' he said in a 1985 address in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. In May, the pontiff received Anglican archbishop and 1984 Nobel Peace Prize winner <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, who defiantly invited arrest and prosecution Sunday by urging a boycott of Oct. 26 municipal elections in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>'s challenge to the government came two days after the South African law and order minister, <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>, said the time had come to `` clip the wings'' of church leaders who hide behind the `` mask of liberation theology.'' Earlier this week, police armed with a search warrant seized a tape of <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>'s sermon at the archbishop's <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> office. When the pope greeted <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> and other South African clergymen in May, he said the system of racial segregation has exacted a `` terrible toll.'' <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> urged tougher sanctions by Western nations _ an issue on which the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> has not taken a position. South African Roman Catholic bishops, who have worked closely with Anglicans, were waiting for the pope at his first stop in the <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> capital of <LOCATION> Harare </LOCATION>. They are attending a conference of regional bishops there. After a meeting with <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>, the pope planned to address the 71 bishops in a Dominican convent. The speech, one of 42 drafted during a summer vacation in the mountains, was expected to set the tone for the 12,400-mile voyage. In a document issued two years ago, the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> said it was perfectly legitimate for the oppressed to take action _ such as passive resistance _ to secure structures and institutions in which their rights would be respected. But it warned clergy against direct involvement in politics and against any efforts to inject Marxism into church work on behalf of the poor.
