<TEXT>
 Two West German doctors are believed to have been captured in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by the communist government as they sought to help wounded guerrilla soldiers, a private aid official said Saturday. <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramdohr </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> German </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Doctors </ORGANIZATION>, said Moslem guerrillas reported a man and a woman from the group were apprehended by Afghan communist authorities in the southeastern provincial capital of <LOCATION> Ghazni </LOCATION>. `` We can not confirm it 100 percent. We have had no news from the German embassy,'' <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramdohr </PERSON> said. He declined to identify the two but said they were about a week overdue returning from a trip to the central Afghan province of <LOCATION> Bamyan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramdohr </PERSON> said a guerrilla source reported that the pair was driving toward <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> with a wounded rebel and a translator when they lost their way and accidentally strayed into communist-controlled territory. The Germans and their wounded charge were apprehended, but the translator fled, according to the report. He said guerrillas believed the couple were flown to <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> Friday or Saturday. German embassy officials were unavailable for comment as the mission was closed for the weekend. Soviet troops have been helping the Afghan government fight the U.S.-backed guerrillas since December 1979. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> agreed in April to withdraw its estimated 115,000 troops by February 1989.
