<HEAD>Supreme Court's Ideological Balance at Stake in November</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf bgng, _Lawrence, to CORRECT, reading Laurence
instead Lawrence.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At stake in the voters' choice between <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in November is the delicate balance between liberal and conservative justices that has set the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s ideological course in recent years. When the next president takes office, the three oldest and most liberal justices on the nine-member high court will be over 80. The average age of the court's liberal wing will be a bit over 77. The average age of its conservative bloc will be 59. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> almost certainly would appoint far more conservative justices as president than <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would. Four years ago, there were predictions that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would have the chance to decide the future of an aging <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> for generations to come, but things did n't work out that way. There is no question that the court is younger and more conservative than it was at the start of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s second term. But liberal justices still exert critical influence, and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s opportunity to turn the court into a conservative stronghold has passed In this election year, however, predictions of sweeping changes in the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in the next four years seem more likely to come true. The nine justices enjoy lifetime tenure. None is reported to have grave health problems, and none has made any public mention of retirement plans. The court's leading liberals are Justices <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, 82, <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, 80, and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON>, soon to be 80. Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, 68, often joins them, particularly in criminal law decisions. The court's conservative bloc is led by Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON>, 63. Its most conservative member is <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON>, 52. In varying degrees, the conservatives are bolstered by Justices <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, 58, <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, 52, and <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, 71. Unlike <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> nominee <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> in 1984, the two presidential candidates this year have virtually ignored the high court and their vision of its future in their stump speeches. Vice President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has noted that the next president `` will very possibly appoint two or three justices to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, where they'll sit well into the next century.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> promises to appoint judges `` who will interpret the Constitution, not legislate from the bench.'' He also says he will `` appoint judges who do n't reserve all their sympathy for criminals; who understand that victims have rights, too.'' The unspoken message appears to be that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, like <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, is determined to select conservative justices who could sway the high court's balance of power on such issues as abortion and affirmative action. The court for years has been drifting toward more conservative views regarding the rights of criminal suspects. As governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has appointed numerous judges who generally have been more liberal than conservative. However, they are screened by an 18-member, non-ideological `` merit commission.'' Speculation about the impact that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> or <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> might have on the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> depends on who they would nominate and which justices would be replaced. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> named <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> to the court in 1981. Since 1984, he has appointed <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. All three are more conservative then the men they replaced, but <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> did not have a chance to place a conservative in a seat formerly held by a liberal. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> succeeded <PERSON> Potter </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> was a numerical replacement for retired Chief Justice <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burger </PERSON> after <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> was elevated to chief justice, and <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> succeeded retired Justice <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> recently asked 40 court observers _ including campaign officials, former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aides, federal judges, law professors and lawyers _ to speculate on possible nominees of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. The 10 people named most often as potential <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> nominees, in alphabetical order, were: _ <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, 58, former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> chief of staff who is the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign chairman _ C <PERSON> Boyden </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, 45, the vice president's legal adviser since 1981. _ <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, 54, a Republican senator from <LOCAT