<HEAD>Agreement On Missiles, Satellites Highlight Carlucci Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANGHAI, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> on Saturday wrapped up his visit to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, leaving the Chinese happy about a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision that could permit Chinese rockets to launch <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> satellites. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> also said he was satisfied that the Chinese would exercise prudence in their arms sales to the Middle East and other areas of the world. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said he conveyed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision about satellites to National Defense Minister <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiwei </PERSON>. `` He was most pleased with that,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> told reporters at the <ORGANIZATION> Wusong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Facility </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration on Friday announced it would give export licenses for satellites manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> that are scheduled to be launched for Australian and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> companies with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s Long March rocket. The decision must be approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and a group of Western allies that monitor high-technology transfers. Hong Kong-based AsiaSat is to put a satellite in orbit next year, while <ORGANIZATION> AusSat </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> will launch two satellites in 1991 and 1992 using the Chinese service. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said he had recommended to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that the licenses be approved. The settling of the satellite issue was the second major area of friction solved during <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>'s first trip to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. In <LOCAT