<HEAD>Asian Officials Regret Passage Of U.S. Textile Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Japanese official said Saturday he hopes President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will veto a bill approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to curb textile imports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` It is regrettable that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved the bill, ignoring the fact that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> textile exports have increased and the industry did not perform as badly as many people believed,'' said <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> <PERSON> Chang-han </PERSON>, acting secretary general of the <ORGANIZATION> Taiwan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Textile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, by a 57-32 vote, Friday approved new curbs on textile, clothing and shoe imports. The bill still needs approval by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> before it can be sent to President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. The bill would freeze this year's imports of textiles, apparel and non-rubber footwear at 1987 levels and limit their growth to 1 percent annually thereafter. `` We hope President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will veto the bill if it is passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> said. `` Such a protectionist measure will only hurt American consumers who would have to pay higher prices for textile products.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s largest market for textile goods. Last year, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s apparel and textile exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> totaled $ 3.2 billion, up 14 percent from 1986. During a meeting in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> Saturday with visiting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Comme