<HEAD>Salinas Confirmed As Mexico's Next President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDAJOY FENLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After a long and bitter debate, the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> today certified <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON> as president of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. A spokesman for the chamber said the vote was 263-85. Opposition lawmakers, who claim <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> won the July 6 election through massive vote fraud, tried to stall the certification process by making numerous speeches during an all-night session. But they had no chance of prevailing. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> will begin a six-year term Dec. 1 and replace <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>. The raucous debate occurred because the election placed the largest number of opposition lawmakers in the legislature since the governing <ORGANIZATION> Institutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>, was founded nearly 60 years ago. As expected, today's vote was along party lines. <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION>, won a majority of 260 in the 500-person chamber in the election, and at least three opposition deputies have since defected to the governing party. <PERSON> Orlando </PERSON> <PERSON> Arvizu </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> PRI </ORGANIZATION> deputy from <LOCATION> Hidalgo </LOCATION> state, said Friday evening the chamber debate would continue `` until we certify the presidential election.'' `` If it's up to us, it -LRB- the confirmation -RRB- could last three days. We plan to destroy their arguments one by one,'' said a Popular Socialist spokesman. The <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> belongs to the left-of-center <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> coalition </ORGANIZATION> h