<FIRST>r w AM-Byrd-Text     09-10 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Byrd-Text,770</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is the text of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> response to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s radio address Saturday, given by Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>: This week millions of American children went back to These young people represent <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future. Today, I want to take issue with what the president has been saying about education. Let's set the record straight. For seven years now the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration have been working on our arithmetic. The administration subtracts from education. The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adds to save it. For seven years now we Democrats have been trying to educate the administration about the value of education. It has n't helped. I'm not surprised. This White House has never had a real commitment to excellence in education. I do n't understand why the administration has n't done its homework. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future economic prosperity depends on having the best educated workforce in the world. Put simply, an educated <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is a strong <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Just two days ago the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Competitiveness </ORGANIZATION> stated that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is developing an `` ominous'' dependence on foreign professors and researchers. Forty percent of all engineering students graduating from American colleges and universities are now foreign-born. We now import brains and intellectual talent the same way that we import cars and radios. Why do we rely so heavily on foreign talent? Because our schools are not teaching our children the math and science skills they need for our new high-tech economy. And that's not all. According to a recent survey, 75 percent of all American students could not locate the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> on a world map. The alarm has been sounded again and again. Yet nothing has been done by the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to link <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s economic future to rebuilding our nation's educational system. Nothing at all. This White House talks a lot about the three R's. But when it comes to helping education, their three R's amount to rhetoric, reductions and retrenchment. If the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had its way, <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> grants would be cut by 40 percent, college work study programs would end, vocational education would stop altogether, and aid to graduate school students would come to a halt. Even the `` drug free'' school program would be cut by 50 percent. My friends, this is terribly wrong. It used to be that a high-school diploma was the guarantee of a good job and the chance to marry and settle down. Now, even our high school graduates are struggling. Put simply, you ca n't get ahead unless you have the best education possible. But getting a good college education is almost out of reach for these young Americans and for millions of other Americans. There are hundreds of thousands of middle-class families struggling to make ends meet, so they can send their children to college. They want their children to get ahead _ to be a part of an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> dream. But in the last seven years their sacrifice has gone unrewarded. Even though college tuitions have risen by 60 percent since 1981, again and again the administration has tried to cut student aid. I have had to vote 14 times in the last seven years to protect student loan programs. Fourteen times! And, when it comes to doing something about adult illiteracy, the White House blackboard is completely blank. Twenty-three million Americans are now functionally illiterate. How difficult it must be to live a life when you can not read and write; when you can not read the Bible, or a story to your children, or even the funny pages in the newspaper. Yet, these illiterate Americans are the very Americans who can make the difference, if <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is to stay No. 1. If we want <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to be strong in every way, we need to recognize that smart students are just as important as smart weapons. In my home state of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, the students who answered my annual survey know that too! Forty percent of them rated education as the first priority of the federal government. We need leadership in the White House that appreciates the value of education as much as do the young people of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. I am encouraged that at least one of the presidential candidates has made a pledge that no college student should be turned away from college because they ca n't get financial aid. The education formula for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future prosperity is clear: good schools equal a smart workforce and that adds up to an <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> that is still the best. Let's do our homework now, so we do n't flunk later. In this course <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> ca n't afford to fail. Thank you and may God bless you.
</TEXT>
