<HEAD>Indian Businessman Flys Ultralight 6,000 Miles In 23 Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NILOVA ROY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A millionaire grandfather landed a 330-pound airplane in his homeland Saturday after a 23-day flight from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> that set a record for ultralight aviation. <PERSON> Vijaypat </PERSON> <PERSON> Singhania </PERSON>'s ultralight plane made a perfect landing at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Safdarjung </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> at 11:10 a.m. <PERSON> Singhania </PERSON>, 49, took off from <LOCATION> Biggin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Kent </LOCATION> on Aug. 18. The red-and-white fiberglass aircraft flew 6,000 miles through high winds and sandstorms and over hundreds of miles of open sea. <PERSON> Singhania </PERSON> said he fought depression, heat sores and a steady weight loss in the hours spent in the cramped cockpit of the cone-shaped plane. The 21-feet long plane has a one-half-horsepower engine and a wingspan of 32 feet. Its top speed is about 60 mph. `` Flying at 10,000 feet over the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION>, I saw ships and tried to visualize how long it would take for them to pick me up if I fell in,'' the bespectacled, balding industrialist said at the airport. `` I had a lifejacket strapped on, shark repellent by my side and kept talking to my granddaughter's picture that was strapped on to the front of my cockpit to keep myself from going crazy.'' He said he lost 24 pounds during the trip. <PERSON> Singhania </PERSON>, the head of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s third-largest business group, beat a 34-day speed record set over the same course this year by a British television journalist, <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Milton </PERSON>. <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> to greet <PERSON> Singhania </PERSON> at the end of the flight. `` There have been only five long flights -LRB- above 5,000 miles -RRB- undertaken in a microlight aircraft,'' he said. `` Anyone who attempts such a flight will have to beat <PERSON> Vijay </PERSON> to make the record.'' The plane is named L'Espirit d'Indian Post, after a Bombay-based newspaper owned by the Singhania group. <PERSON> Singhania </PERSON> said the name was a combination of his `` two passions'' _ the spirit of adventure and his newspaper. `` I wanted to try and break the record. I wanted to be an ambassador for my country and show people <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> is not just a country of snake charmers,'' he said. `` I am very proud to have established <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> on the aviation map and feel tremendously thrilled that I managed to so positively portray the indomitable spirit latent in all men, the spirit of adventure,'' <PERSON> Singhania </PERSON> said. `` And not least of all, I was running out of stories to tell my grandchildren _ now I have a fund of tales.''
