<HEAD>Another 4,000 Jobs Go; Incredible Shrinking Airline?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Money-losing <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> eliminated 4,000 more jobs Saturday in the `` downsizing'' it says it needs to survive, but the unions charged that the cutbacks are actually making the airline less competitive. The cuts, which are being contested in court by the unions, reduced <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s workforce to fewer than 30,000. Less than four years ago, it had 42,000 workers. Eastern eliminated 12 percent of its routes two weeks ago, ending service to 14 cities. Laid-off workers with seniority can transfer to other cities, `` bumping'' newer employees out of their jobs. Thus, newer employees could take the brunt of the layoffs when the bumping is complete. The mood around work gates was sullen. `` We've had very few who have already gotten their layoff notices, but we've heard there are about 80 who have shown intentions of bumping,'' said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON>, a union chief steward representing ramp agents. `` So a lot of these people do n't know what to expect.'' `` The people are devastated,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, president of the Machinists local, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s largest union with nearly 12,000 members. `` It's a traumatic thing to lose your job when you've just gotten your children started in school.'' Of the 4,000 jobs eliminated, 1,500 were non-union positions, including management and clerical. Among the 4,000 are few hundred flight attendants, mechanics, baggage handlers and ramp agents who are taking early retirement or quitting, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The fact is we have lost over a billion dollars in this decade,'' said <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON>, the company's chief spokesman. `` We have to take prudent, although admittedly painful, measures.'' Eastern, which lost $ 182 million in 1987 and $ 149 million in the first half of 1988 and is $ 2.5 billion in debt, estimates it will save $ 100 million a year with the latest cuts. Eastern was taken over more than two years ago by Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Union members have accused <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> of stripping <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s assets in favor of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s sister airline, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, which has been non-union since <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> took it into bankruptcy reorganization in 1983 The unions say downsizing the carrier dooms Eastern to decreasing ability to compete. Laying off employees drives up labor costs per flight because less-senior workers being laid off are paid less than those who remain, they said. `` The last thing you want to do in the airline industry is downsize,'' <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> said. `` Many of the costs are fixed, and the break-even yield goes way up. It's a lose-lose proposition that just feeds on itself. `` <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> is using typical robber baron strategy to plunder the company and try to make all the cash he can.'' Eastern's unions will argue against the layoffs later this month in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, which allowed <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> to cut the jobs if it posted a $ 4.7 million bond to cover wages if workers are later reinstated. The appeals court earlier his month set aside an injunction by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Barrington </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, who had barred Eastern from eliminating the jobs without negotiating with its unions. Machinists' members will vote Thursday on a management demand for $ 161 million in cuts. The union and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> have been in federal mediation since January.
