<HEAD>Presidential Yacht Comes To Boston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IAN DONNIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fancied by <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON>, sold by <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and ignored by <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, the presidential yacht Sequoia is on the last leg of a 120-city fund-raising tour before it is returned to White House control. The Sequoia was bought by the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> from a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> family in 1929. After <PERSON> Hoover </PERSON> wintered on the boat in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> in 1933, it was acquired by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and declared the official presidential yacht. The 105-foot vessel served eight presidents over a period of 44 years before <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> ordered the ship sold at auction in 1977 as an austerity move. `` The Sequoia is really a symbol of the presidency in the 20th century,'' said <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> McGehee </PERSON>, spokesman for The <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yacht </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION>, the private group that bought the ship and began restoring it in 1981. <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> planned war strategy from the ship, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON> used it for the first international conference on nuclear arms control and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> held working sessions with the likes of Soviet leader <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> on board, <PERSON> McGehee </PERSON> said. The ship was open for public visits over the weekend at the <ORGANIZATION> Charlestown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yard </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. It will make more stops along the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> before it is donated to the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> on Nov. 15 and again becomes the presidential yacht. The fund-raising voyage has raised $ 5.5 million, half the $ 11 million needed for restoration costs and to create an endowment for future maintenance and operations without taxpayer expense, he said. But <PERSON> McGehee </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has failed to stamp his imprimatur on the project. `` This is the ultimate private sector project,'' he said. `` One would think <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would be willing to hold this up and say, ` This is what I've been talking about.''' <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> used the lure of an afternoon cruise on the ship to entangle legislators in marathon discussions and hold them hostage until they came around to his point of view, <PERSON> McGehee </PERSON> said. `` We've had some funny stories about senators and congressmen telling the captain to turn the boat around and go back to dock. The captain would say he could only listen to his commander-in-chief.'' <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> enjoyed taking cruises on the <LOCATION> Potomac </LOCATION> in the Sequoia and announced his decision to resign the presidency to his family aboard the ship. A joint congressional resolution in 1985 provided for the Sequoia's eventual return, and the ship was designated a National Historic Landmark earlier this year. <PERSON> McGehee </PERSON> said the Presidential Yacht Trust has spent $ 3.5 million restoring teak paneling, bleached ash interiors, handmade carpets, engines and other details. The ship was built for $ 210,000, but to build it now would cost between $ 8 million and $ 10 million.
</TEXT>
