<HEAD>Newspaper Says Investigation Shows Jetliner Hit By Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Experts have concluded that an Italian jetliner which mysteriously crashed into a sea eight years ago, killing all 81 people on board, was shot down by missile, a newspaper reported. British and American experts have been analyzing the recently salvaged wreckage of the DC-9, which exploded and crashed into the <LOCATION> Tyrrhenian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> on June 27, 1980. The Italian government financed a salvage operation to raise the fuselage so experts could determine the cause of the disaster. The Milan newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Corriere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> della </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sera </ORGANIZATION> said that British explosives experts and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> engineers at <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the jetliner's manufacturer, have determined the plane was downed by a missile. The paper said the missile exploded seconds before it would have struck the jetliner. It said the blast destroyed the cockpit, killed the flight crew, damaged the baggage compartment door on the right, scorched the outside of the plane and punched three grapefruit-size holes in the fuselage. The same newspaper reported in June that experts were certain the airliner had been hit by a missile. But a member of the investigating commission later denied it had reached any conclusions. <PERSON> Corriere </PERSON> <PERSON> della </PERSON> <PERSON> Sera </PERSON> said on Friday that the experts completed their investigation Thursday and that the results were being forwarded to Judge <PERSON> Vittorio </PERSON> <PERSON> Bucarelli </PERSON>, who is in charged of the inquiry. The newspaper said the voice recorder on the flight picked up an undecipherable shout just before the explosion. It also said the British experts are still trying to determine the chemical composition of the explosive as a way to trace the nationality of the missile. The plane was on a flight from <LOCATION> Bologna </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Palermo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION>. It crashed in the sea 30 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION>, between the islands of <LOCATION> Ponza </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ustica </LOCATION>.
