<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's largest labor federation on Saturday rejected a government appeal to call off another general strike and said the work stoppage will be held to protest police repression. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> said its unions will hold a 24-hour nationwide strike on Monday. It had organized an 8-hour general strike Friday to protest the gpvernment's economic policies and police used tear gas, rubber bullets and clubs to disperse about 20,000 demonstrators at a rally in downtown <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>. `` The Monday strike is unchangeable and there will be no modification,'' <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> Ubaldini </PERSON>, secretary-general of the labor federation, told reporters as he arrived at a union meeting to discuss Friday's violence. He said Monday's strike would be `` a peaceful repudiation'' of police actions Friday. Federal police said Saturday that 76 demonstrators and 37 policemen were injured during the disturbances in the Plaza de Mayo. They reported four civilians and eight policemen were hospitalized for fractures and cuts. Thirteen demonstrators were arrested and face charges of assault, resisting arrest, arson and vandalism, according to the report. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> had appealed to the labor federation to reconsider its call for a Monday strike. It said police intervened in the <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> rally to halt vandalism and fighting between rival union groups. But <PERSON> Ubdaldini </PERSON> said, `` It's a lie that the incidents began among participants of the rally.'' Interior Minister <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Nosiglia </PERSON> issued a communique saying violence `` can only benefit small anti-democratic sectors.'' `` Nothing can justify a new paralyzation of the country that will only postpone progress without providing any benefit for rights and freedoms,'' it said. Monday's strike will be the 13th organized by the General Labor Confederation since the elected government of President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> and his centrist <ORGANIZATION> Radical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> came to power Dec. 10, 1983, ending nearly eight years of military rule. The labor federation is dominated by the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Both <PERSON> Nosiglia </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Pirker </PERSON> rejected union charges of police brutality and blamed agitators for the violence. <PERSON> Ubaldini </PERSON>, who fled the platform at the Plaza de Maya rally Friday in a cloud of tear gas, had described the strike as `` a peoples' referendum against the plan of hunger and misery that they -LRB- the government -RRB- want to impose on us.'' He referred to an anti-inflation plan introduced by the government last month that devalued the currency, lifted restrictions on some imports and called for voluntary wage and price controls. Inflation has registered 255 percent so far this this year and 440 percent during the past 12 months.
