<HEAD>Discovery Of Mercury Could Threaten Plans For New Wildlife Refuge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The discovery of mercury in freshwater marshes in eastern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> has complicated plans to turn the area into the <ORGANIZATION> Bayou </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sauvage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> told city and state officials Thursday that they discovered quantities of mercury well above federal health levels near a landfill that has a history of leaking into the surrounding marshes. The city-owned Recovery I landfill is operated by <ORGANIZATION> Waste </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and a company spokesman denied the landfill was the source of the mercury contamination. The Fish and Wildlife report said it found only mercury, not pesticides or petroleum hydrocarbons. The report said additional samples have been taken to confirm the mercury findings, and those results should be available in October. Officials said the mercury contamination poses no immediate health hazard. The marshland near the landfill is not used for commercial fishing or hunting, and since mercury is a heavy metal, it tends to sink and combine with sediment at the bottom of the marsh. Wildlife Service officials already were concerned that about 1,500 acres of marshland near the landfill was depleted of oxygen, a symptom of chemical and biological contaminants, and was not supporting wildlife. City officials had been negotiating with federal officials to see if an airport could be constructed near the proposed refuge. The questions raised by the <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> test results will slow down those negotiations, city officials said. City officials said they are n't convinced the landfill is the source of the contamination, and suggested the mercury might be from a spill from railroad tank cars on tracks that cut across the property. No such spill has been reported. Planning Commission Director <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Becker </PERSON> said city consultants also do n't understand why the test results turned up no other contaminants, when a mixture of contaminants would be more likely to escape from a landfill. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> officials said they will review the Recovery I operating permit, which expires Oct. 17. City officials have notified the state that they do n't plan to renew <ORGANIZATION> Waste </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>'s contract to operate the facility, although <ORGANIZATION> Waste </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> requested a 10-year extension of its state permit last year. The city wants to put operation of the landfill out to bid, and has asked the state for a seven-year grace period to continue to dispose household garbage in the landfill before shutting it down.
