<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Commodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazard </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>'s brigantine <LOCATION> Niagara </LOCATION> returned to the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> on Saturday, exactly 175 years after his fleet defeated the British in the Battle of <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION>. `` We are starting a new page in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s history, and you all are a part of it,'' Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> told an estimated 5,000 people gathered for the launching ceremony. <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON>, lifted a bottle of <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> wine and struck the 182-foot, 278-ton restored ship, bedecked with the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flag and <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>'s battle flag, `` Do n't Give Up the Ship.'' The bottle did n't break, however, and she had to strike the ship again, this time successfully. Shortly afterward, a crane lifted the ship into <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Presque </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Isle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> Eighteen cannons fired a military salute, and more than 200 private boats anchored in the bay to watch the festivities blared their horns. It was the fourth time the ship had been restored, this time using $ 3.8 million in state and private funds. The restored <LOCATION> Niagara </LOCATION> will be outfitted by next spring with 118-foot and 113-foot masts, square rigging, about 22,000 square feet of polyester sail and 20 aluminum cannon. It will then tour the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> ports as <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s `` official flagship.'' The first USS Niagara was one of six small ships built in this port city during the War of 1812 and put under <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>'s command to break a British blockade of American Great Lakes ports and to defend the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Territory </LOCATION>. On Sept. 10, 1813, <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>'s nine-ship squadron met six British vessels under Commodore <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Heriot </PERSON> <PERSON> Barclay </PERSON> in a short but fierce battle near <LOCATION> Put-in-Bay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>'s flagship, the USS Lawrence, was disabled by British fire. <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> transferred to the <LOCATION> Niagara </LOCATION>, where he hoisted his famous battle flag, `` Do n't Give up the Ship,'' and attacked again. The Niagara helped break the British battle line and forced <PERSON> Barclay </PERSON> to surrender. `` We have met the enemy and they are ours: two ships, two brigs, one schooner and one sloop,'' <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> reported to his superiors. The <LOCATION> Niagara </LOCATION> served as a station ship in <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION> until 1820, when it was scuttled in nearby Misery Bay. The ship was raised by <PERSON> Erie </PERSON> citizens in 1913 and restored for a Great Lakes tour to celebrate the 100th anniversary of <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>'s victory. The ship was restored again in the 1930s and 1940s. In the latest restoration, <PERSON> Melbourne </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, marine architect, dismantled the <LOCATION> Niagara </LOCATION> and rebuilt it to historical specifications. Forty-two pieces of the original ship are incorporated in the restored brigantine.
