picks up 8th pvs: Among the...; Deletes last five grafs and edits
throughout to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and other Solidarity leaders Saturday demanded an end to government reprisals against workers who went on strike and said authorities should be prepared to consider legalizing the labor group. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, key Solidary advisers and other activists gathered in a <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> to plan their strategy for talks with authorities on the future of the outlawed labor movement. They issued a statement late Saturday saying they wanted confirmation that authorities are prepared to `` create conditions'' for legalizing Solidarity, which was suspended in 1981 and subsequently outlawed. The weekend conference is one of the largest gatherings of the Polish opposition in years. The meeting Saturday included Solidarity regional leaders and strike committee members, and a gathering Sunday is to include intellectuals and cultural figures who advise Solidarity founder <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>. The group is meeting to discuss the communist government's offer to enter negotiations. On Aug. 31, authorities agreed to open talks and <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> agreed to end a 19-day wave of strikes. <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Stelmachowski </PERSON>, a Roman Catholic intellectual acting as a mediator between the governent and opposition, said he expected the gpvermment-Solidarity talks would begin in the middle of the week. Diplomatic sources said they were told the meeting would begin Sept. 15. At the end of Saturday's meeting the Solidarity leadership released a statement saying: `` We expect a clear expression by the Polish authorities of readiness to create conditions for legal functioning of Solidarity. `` Only the legalization of Solidarity allows the effective participation of the union in reforming the country.'' The statement also demanded an end to reprisals against workers who had participated in strikes. Actions such as detentions, firings and induction of strike participants into the military `` impair the credibility of the authorities' proposals,'' it said. `` We expect an immediate end to repressions.'' Union activists have reported about 350 miners were fired following strikes in the coal region of southern poland and dozens of other workers received army draft notices. Solidarity sources, speaking with the condition of anonymity, said the statement should not be considered an ultimatum and the round-table talks could begin even without official gestures. <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON>, an adviser to <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, said Solidarity wanted a signal from authorities that the talks could be held `` in serious conditions with a chance for success.'' <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> said <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and representatives of four regional strike committees would represent Solidarity at the talks with the government. Saturday's meeting was held at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brygida </ORGANIZATION>'s church near the Lenin shipyard where Solidarity was born in 1980 amid nationwide strikes and became the first free trade union in the Soviet bloc. Attending the meeting were the 15-member national executive commission of Solidarity, representatives of strike committees during the Aug. 16-Sept. 3 wave of strikes and members of the interfactory strike committees Among the 40 participants were solidarity advisers such as <PERSON> Jacek </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON>, <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Michnik </PERSON> and <PERSON> Zbigniew </PERSON> <PERSON> Romaszewski </PERSON> who monitor human rights abuses. Nearby in another church, leaders of the banned <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> met and drafted a statement in support of Solidarity. `` I'm surprised by the way these people are prepared,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said during a break in the session. `` There are a lot of fighting people who I expected to represent their fighting manner. And I am surprised by their great feeling of responsibility and great wisdom, especially among the young people.'' Solidarity is seeking to win back the legal status it lost following Polish leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>'s Dec. 13, 1981, martial-law crackdown. Government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> and Politburo member <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Miodowicz </PERSON>, leader of the officially sanctioned trade union OPZZ, last week reiterated the official stand that Solidarity can not be legalized again as a trade federation. But Urban also said officials were entering the talks with no preconditions. Opposition spokesmen said they insist on the legalization of the union, and they want the issue settled before they will engage in talks on the broad range of political and economic problems. The talks to discuss workers' grievances were proposed by Interior Minister Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> during the August strikes, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s worst wave of labor unrest since 1981. When <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> and <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> met Aug. 31 they agreed that the talks could include discussing the future of Solidarity. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> then appealed to his supporters for a speedy end to the remaining strikes so the talks could convene. Col. <PERSON> Stanislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwiatkowski </PERSON>, the chief government pollster, said the authorities have no one to blame but themselves for being forced back into talks with <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and Solidarity. `` Briefly stated, it is the sluggishness of the party and the government which are to blame for the rebirth of Solidarity, whose cadres have begun to count again in the political game,'' <PERSON> Kwiatkowski </PERSON> said in the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Zycie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warszawy </ORGANIZATION>.
