 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> hurled a symbolic pitch Saturday to mark the delivery of a shipment of baseball equipment to Nicaraguans at a refugee camp in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the exchange chairman, said another shipment will be delivered to the refugees later and a third will be given to Hondurans. Baseball has been a popular Nicaraguan sport since the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military intervention in the 1920s. Hundreds of refugees looked wide-eyed at the bats, balls and gloves donated by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> major league baseball teams and sporting goods manufacturers. `` This makes me happy,'' said <PERSON> Sabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Correa </PERSON>, 28, who fled <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> six years ago and at one time was a rebel fighting the Sandinista government. `` Baseball is important to Nicaraguans.'' <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON>, who said he left <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> two years ago to escape being drafted into the army, agreed. He said the camp at <LOCATION> Jacaleapa </LOCATION> has four adult basebll teams and two junior leagues. `` There's not much else to do,'' he said. The 517 helmets, 2,400 gloves, 1,600 bats, 800 caps, 700 balls and 500 T-shirts delivered Saturday by a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military transport plane will be shared among 13,000 Nicaraguans in three U.N.-run refugee camps in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON>, who is co-chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commisson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recovery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGAN