rignts movement is dead and he always says no. `` The nature and the character of the movement has changed, but these changes are merely part of a natural process and do not spell doom for our hopes,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people must elect leaders with the `` moral capacity'' of the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> if civil rights are to improve with time. `` There are going to be some setbacks,'' he said. `` But we are going to move toward the beloved community; we are going to make it as a people and as a nation.''
