<HEAD>Museum Gets 3-D Look at 2,500-Year-Old Mummy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Children's Museum sent its 2,500-year-old mummy to the hospital Saturday to learn more about the ancient woman from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. During her visit to <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, Wenu-hotep got her picture taken with a three-dimensional CT scan that provided a never-before-seen view of her face. `` We found much finer pictures than I would have expected of the bones. These were incredibly clear and detailed images of the skull, the tissues, the internal bones of the skull,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON>, curator of anthropology for the museum. <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> said the X-rays could be used later as the basis for artistic renderings to show what <PERSON> Wenu-hotep </PERSON>'s face looked like. The physical anthropologist said the scan also showed in detail the hole used to remove Wenu-hotep's brain during the mummification process, as well as resins and linen wrappings used to preserve the body. `` We also cleared up an old problem,'' he said. `` In X-rays taken about 1967 it appears there was a fracture of the left hip. We were able to show pretty conclusively there was not a fracture of the hip. In fact the hip appears to be normal.'' Interest in Wenu-hotep has increased dramatically in the two weeks since <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yurco </PERSON>, a Egyptological consultant from the <LOCATION> Field </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, performed new studies on her. Until then, scholars thought Wenu-hotep and her family were only of minor importance. But <PERSON> Yurco </PERSON> discovered that she was a pivotal mummy, meaning she provides totally new information about ancient <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Yurco </PERSON>'s detailed readings of the art and hieroglyphics on the coffin indicate Wenu-hotep's father, Hor-em-hat, was a h