<FIRST>a i PM-SahelRains Adv15   09-10 0950</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sahel Rains, Adv 15,0975</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs Sept. 15 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Best Rains in Years Promise Good Harvests in Drought-Ravaged Sahel</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>BY ROBERT WELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARMA, Niger (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Biba </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdou </PERSON>'s children, all skin and bones, were smiling from ear-to-ear as they played beside the family's 10-food-high millet crop, the best they had ever seen `` My boys are skinny now, but soon they will be fat,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Biba </PERSON>, whose family farms near <LOCATION> Karma </LOCATION>, about 35 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION>'s capital, <LOCATION> Niamey </LOCATION>. `` We have never seen rain like this. We are very content.'' For the moment, a drought-weary people have reason to smile. All across <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s Sahel, abundant rains promise the best harvest in two decades. Nothing comes easy in the Sahel, a huge belt of land on the southern fringe of the <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>, and the good rains are no exception. More than 100 lives were lost in torrential rains, thousands of homes destroyed and some farmland flooded. An infestation of locusts also threatens some crops, although the most immediate threat appears to be to the east in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> rose to levels higher than any recorded in August since record-keeping began in 1928. Scientists at a <LOCATION> Niamey </LOCATION> agricultural weather center, set up to monitor conditions in nine Sahel nations after the disastrous 1972-73 drought, report the plentiful rain promises good harvests. Good pasturage is available for cattle, goats, sheep. The Sahel region is generally defined as covering the land south of the <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> with annual rainfall averaging from six to 24 inches. It stretches from <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mali </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION> in the north into northern <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION> in the south. Many Sahel regions had already received more than 14 inches, the amount needed for millet crops, by the end of August. More important, the rain had continued to fall since the beginning of June. The crop needs rainfall throughout its three-month growth for the best harvests. The Sahel nations _ <PERSON> Burkina </PERSON> <PERSON> Faso </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verde </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mauritania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mali </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bissau </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gambia </LOCATION> _ have suffered recurring drought or generally inadequate rainfall since 1972. The nine nations cover more than 2 million square miles and have a population of about 40 million. <PERSON> Amadou </PERSON> <PERSON> Djibo </PERSON>, who farms with his father and three brothers about 60 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Niamey </LOCATION>, said people were n't concerned about losing their homes or flooding that had temporarily cut off an important road. Like the marabou storks who circled overhead, the rains were considered a harbinger of better days. `` We can always rebuild a house, but if we have no rain, we have no food,'' he said. <PERSON> Djibo </PERSON> added that his village of <LOCATION> Zarakoire </LOCATION>, had not had an adequate harvest in seven years and life was hard. <PERSON> Boukar </PERSON> <PERSON> Elhadj </PERSON> <PERSON> Ousmane </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION>'s minister in charge of animal and water resources, said the rains had left 13 people dead and 7,000 homeless. He also reported 15,000 animals, including goats, sheep and cattle, lost and about 600 miles of roads left temporarily impassable. Heavy rainfall has been reported across <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, extending into <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> where torrential rains and flooding resulted in 96 deaths and $ 200 million in damage. In the Sahel, <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION> reported 45 people dead and 48,000 homeless and 3,500 cattle lost. More than 50 people were killed in northern <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and thousands left homeless; two dams burst after the heaviest rainfalls in 50 years. <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Burkina </PERSON> <PERSON> Faso </PERSON> also reported several deaths and many houses destroyed. Much flood damage was reported near rivers, where people had moved in close to the water during drought years to plant gardens. <PERSON> Boukar </PERSON> said he could understand the attitude of peasants who minimized the importance of the damage, and said, `` We can consider the rain a blessing.'' He added, `` It gives them hope for the future. Many of those people have never seen this kind of rain in their lives. They have only heard stories about it.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Eaton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION>'s director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- AID -RRB-, which was still distributing food donated to meet shortfalls from the last harvest, said <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION>'s food situation should be good after this harvest. `` That's if the locusts do n't eat it all, or if there is so much there is still enough for the people.'' <PERSON> Eaton </PERSON> said he had received reports of good harvest prospects from AID directors in other Sahel nations. `` This has been a great morale booster, even with the locust threat,'' he added. `` People are upbeat.'' Some harvesting already has begun in southern <LOCATION> Sahel </LOCATION> regions, where crops mature earlier. But in most areas millet, sorghum and other crops will be harvested in the coming weeks. No one predicts an end to food shortages, though given the probable reduction in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> food aid because of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drought the Sahel rains were timely. Each Sahel country has its own troubles, and the rain certainly would create some problems, even if it alleviated others. And no one predicts that the drought cycle had been broken by the rains. Indeed, scientists here would make no predictions at all, noting a meterological institute had predicted three months ago that the Sahel would experience a very dry year this year. Aid workers expressed concern the good rains will encourage pastoralists to rebuild their herds, cut by as much as 50 percent by the massive 1984 drought, to sizes the land ca n't support. Overgrazing has been a key factor in desertification, the process by which the <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION> claims land. A pastoralist's herd remains his bank and chief wealth in the <LOCATION> Sahel </LOCATION> and governments have had little success dissuading their herdsmen from overgrazing the fragile land.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs Sept. 15</NOTE>
