<SECOND>PM-Puerto Rico-Vote, Adv 16,0752</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs Sept. 16 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Puerto Rican Election Focuses on Commonwealth Status</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Puerto Ricans vote for a governor, legislators, mayors and a non-voting member of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on the same day mainland Americans pick a new president. But an underlining issue here is the seemingly never-ending debate over the island's 36-year-old commonwealth relationship with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>'s three main political parties _ distinguished from each other primarily by their support for commonwealth, statehood or independence _ all are seeking changes in what some of them see as the island's semicolonial status. The outcome of elections here Nov. 8 is likely to hinge more on personalities and issues such as unemployment than on <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>'s political status, analysts say But both incumbent governor, <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Colon </PERSON>, the commonwealth candidate, and his statehood rival, Mayor <PERSON> Baltasar </PERSON> <PERSON> Corrada </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Rio </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, have pledged to hold a status referendum after the election. The issue has featured prominently in the campaign so far. It would be the first such referendum since 1967, when 60 percent of the voters favored a continuation of the commonwealth arrangement, 39 percent statehood and 1 percent independence. <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, an island of 3.3 million mostly Spanish-speaking people 1,000 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, has flown the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag since 1898, when <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> ceded it to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at the end of the Spanish-American War. The modern-day commonwealth arrangement, which went into effect in July 1952, gives <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> roughly as much control over its own affairs as any of the 50 states. Puerto Ricans are <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens, but they pay no <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> taxes and can not vote for president. Nevertheless, they are eligible for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military service and Social Security and welfare benefits. <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> receives substantial <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid _ $ 6.5 billion this year alone _ and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies, taking advantage of tax exemptions, have given the island one of the strongest economies in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. In return, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> uses <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> as a strategic base for naval operations and an important market for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods. `` The reality of the relationship, as it is now,'' pro-commonwealth commentator <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maldonado </PERSON> wrote in the English-language <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Juan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION>, `` is enormously beneficial to <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>. Despite monumental efforts of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to cut domestic spending to reduce the gigantic federal deficit, the flow of funds to the island has continued to grow.'' Yet, there is dissatisfaction on all sides. <ORGANIZATION> Commonwealth </ORGANIZATION> supporters want more say in running the island; statehooders complain of being treated as second-class citizens; and the independence movement fervently _ at times violently _ seeks undiluted Puerto Rican sovereignty. <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Colon </PERSON>, 51, who is seeking his third four-year term, favors continued commonwealth status but wants <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to relinquish control over immigration, foreign trade and certain environmental and labor matters. His Popular <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has announced plans for a referendum sometime after the election seeking `` maximum autonomy'' for <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>. But the party has not specified what the term means. <PERSON> Corrada </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Rio </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which wants <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> to become the 51st <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> state, says its referendum would ask voters whether <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> should begin negotiations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on statehood. If approved, the referendum would be followed by a second vote on any negotiated formula. The tiny <ORGANIZATION> Independence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which has n't won more than 6 percent of the vote in 20 years, proposes an election of a multiparty assembly to resolve the sovereignty question and negotiate a solution with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Regardless of the outcome, the election is unlikely to resolve the status issue. The statehood party has twice held the governor's office since it was founded in 1967, but has made no effort to achieve statehood while in power <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON> <PERSON> Colon </PERSON>, who has stressed his administration's economic record rather than the status issue, is favored to win, but it could be close. An opinion poll of 600 registered voters carried out for <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>'s Channel 2 television station in July put the incumbent governor 5 points ahead of <ORGANIZATION> Corrada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> del </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rio </ORGANIZATION> _ 45 percent to 40 percent _ with 4 percent backing the <ORGANIZATION> Independence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Berrios </PERSON> and the rest undecided. The poll had a margin of error of plus or minus 4.3 percent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Sept. 16</NOTE>
