<FIRST>a a PM-Sergio'sProblems ADV13   09-10 0958</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sergio's Problems, ADV 13,0988</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs, Sept. 13, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Child of Poverty Saved From Fire But Faces Years of Surgery</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>APOPKA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five-year-old <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> was lucky to survive a fire that destroyed the small apartment where he lived with his mother and two sisters. And he was fortunate to receive prompt, expert care to treat second - and third-degree burns over most of his face, his hands and chest, and part of his arms and head But <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON>, featured recently in a <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> article looking at the tragic ramifications of living in poverty, is still very much in need. His face was pitifully disfigured by the flames, and he has not regained full movement of his hands. He and his 2-year-old sister, <PERSON> Shakeriay </PERSON>, who was not as seriously injured, spent a month at a Shriners' burn institute in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, after the December incident in this rural <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION> suburb, just a few miles down the road from <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION>. The Newsweek story last month prompted offers of assistance from around the country, some for medical care and reconstructive surgery. A volunteer organization in <LOCATION> Apopka </LOCATION> has set up a fund-raising account for the <ORGANIZATION> Neals </ORGANIZATION>. A 6-year-old girl from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> sent <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> a letter containing two $ 1 bills and two nickels with a note saying: `` Would you please give this to <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON>?'' The fire started after the children's mother, <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Neal </PERSON>, stepped out briefly to a neighboring apartment, leaving <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shakeriay </PERSON> in the living room. One of them evidently played with a cigarette lighter, and fire quickly engulfed the small apartment. Would-be rescuers found one of the doors to the apartment boarded up; they could not get the knob on the other door to work. Hearing the children's screams and frantic, fruitless efforts to open the front door, Ms. <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> and neighbors finally broke through the door, fought the flames and carried the children out just as firefighters arrived. Rescue workers administered emergency medical treatment and rushed them to an <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION> hospital. A day after the blaze, <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> and his sister were flown in separate Learjet ambulances _ complete with a doctor, nurse and medical technician in each plane _ from <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION> to the Shrine facility in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>. After their month's stay, <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> has continued to get outpatient care two or three times a month. All of this expensive, sophisticated treatment has been provided free by the Shriners under their generous programs for needy burned and crippled children around the country. Still, until <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> gets older, there is little doctors can do about his scarred and pitted face. `` Much of the reconstructive surgery has to wait until bone growth stops, probably around the age of 16,'' says <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, children's director of the <ORGANIZATION> Bahia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shrine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Orlando </LOCATION>, who arranged for the <ORGANIZATION> Neals </ORGANIZATION>' treatment, transportation and continuing visits to the <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> facility. `` But we're prepared to help him as long as he needs it, up to the age of 21,'' says <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>. While <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON>'s continuing medical treatment for his physical injuries is ensured, there is some worry about his other, not-so-obvious problems and needs: the mental anguish, which is difficult to determine in a young child; his education, and the home care necessary before plastic surgery. He now wears a plastic face mask, which <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> says puts pressure on facial scar tissue to make it grow sideways to decrease its thickness. Because of his facial disfigurement, his mother is keeping him out of school and hopes to get him on a program that provides a visiting teacher for homebound students. So while other kids his age are starting school, <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> is spending hours in front of a TV or playing and squabbling with his two sisters and four cousins in the two-bedroom apartment where they now live. <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON>'s mother and her three children moved in with her sister <PERSON> Shawana </PERSON> and her four kids after the fire. `` The basic problem is that they are so poor they have no resources for anything,'' says social activist <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> about the <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> family. `` For one thing, here are seven children and two adults living in a tiny apartment. And now the landlord has given them an eviction notice.'' Ms. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, director of a volunteer organization known as SMILE, for Single Mothers In a Learning Experience, said <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Neal </PERSON>'s family would like to move out but ca n't afford to do so `` <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON>'s mother gets less than $ 350 a month in AFDC,'' the state's Aid to Families with Dependent Children, Ms. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said, whereas she'd need an annual income of $ 15,000 to qualify under a federally subsidized low-income housing program. Ms. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> set up the fund-raising account for the <ORGANIZATION> Neals </ORGANIZATION> to help them with housing, and home health care and education for <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON>. Meanwhile, Winter Park attorney <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> <PERSON> Troutman </PERSON>, one of the founders of a legal-aid office for the poor in the <LOCATION> Apopka </LOCATION> area, said he was looking into the possibility of a liability lawsuit over the allegedly defective doorknob in the Neal apartment. `` As I understand it, the kiddies were trying their best to open the door during the fire but the doorknob would n't work,'' he said. `` We're looking into it.'' The <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> case is just one example of how people tend to overlook those in need until disaster strikes, Ms. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said, adding that articles like the one in Newsweek just scratch the surface of the problem. `` I hope we realize poverty is all around us,'' she said, `` that it's not always something hidden behind the scenes.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
