<FIRST>a a PM-GuineaWorm ADV14   09-10 0798</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Guinea Worm, ADV 14,0816</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs, Sept. 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Former President Mounts Campaign Against Debilitating Disease</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note graphic nature of contents.
^By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> is rallying other nations' heads of state and health officials to eradicate a debilitating disease that infects 10 million people and disrupts agriculture in the Third World. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> has also persuaded the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> to target guinea worm disease, which sometimes has fatal complications, as the second disease _ after smallpox _ that the agency seeks to wipe out worldwide. He became concerned about the readily preventable disease through a famine relief program sponsored by Global 2000, a public health foundation headquartered at the <ORGANIZATION> Carter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Presidential </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. The program, whose primary goal is to improve yield for farmers' crops, found that agriculture in many remote areas was hampered because the cyclical worm disease strikes so many people in the spring, sickening them at planting season The disease itself is sickening to describe. In spring, infected people find the worm _ a yard-long, stringlike creature _ painfully emerging from boils that form in soft tissue between the toes or elsewhere on the body, having completed its growth cycle inside its human host. It enters the body through contaminated water. Seeing the ailment's devastation is `` heartrending,'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from his home in Plains. `` And just to realize that, with a simple education program and very simple prevention techiques, this affliction could be eliminated forever.'' Last spring, he and his wife, <PERSON> Rosalynn </PERSON>, visited heavily infected villages in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> nation of <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION>. `` The first village we went to had a population of 500 and they had 213 people stretched out on the ground under the kasha trees for us just to see and to meet,'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said. `` When we talked to the village elders and chiefs, they did n't have any idea what caused guinea worm They thought it might come from the praying mantis or from drinking the blood of goats or from some superstition like the confluence of the planets or that it was a punishment of the gods to test their endurance,'' he said. `` They did n't have any idea it came from drinking filthy water. Then we went down to look at the water hole that was their only source of drinking water. It was covered with scum and the people had to wade out I'd say at least knee deep before they could get a bucket full of water,'' he said. Some of the waders were infected and entered the water to ease their pain. When the emerging guinea worm comes in contact with water, it spews out its larvae which are then eaten by a microscopic animal called a cyclops. Villagers drink the water contaminated with cyclops and the cyclops die in their bodies, leaving behind the larvae to grow into worms. Infections caused when the worm dies inside the body can be fatal, though that is rare, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said. In the first worm eradication program undertaken by Global 2000, in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, foundation workers developed inexpensive techniques for breaking the creature's 12-month life cycle. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said the infestations can be prevented by replacing water holes with deep wells, `` but that costs $ 700 or $ 800 and we do n't have $ 700 or $ 800 for every village in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Other preventive measures include keeping people out of the water holes or having all villagers strain their water for a full year. But widespread illiteracy makes it difficult to educate the people at risk. Still, with the support and participation of the Pakistani government, Global 2000's eradication program is going so well that <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> predicted the disease would be eliminated there by 1990. Full-scale programs have started in <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> in the last year and a new program is about to begin in <LOCATION> Uganda </LOCATION>. `` One of the things that I can contribute as a former president is to go not to an assistant minister of health, who may not have much influence or may not know anything about health to start with, but I go directly to the king or the president or the prime minister and ask him to bring his Cabinet members together,'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said. The news media attention his involvement receives also helps educate potential victims about the disease. `` It's a gratifying thing to see a village that was formerly devastated five or six months a year from guinea worm to emerge after a couple of years with no guinea worm and live a happy, prosperous and healthy life,'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said. `` In the process, to be frank about it, it puts <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> forward as an enlightened, concerned and peace-loving nation.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Sept. 14</NOTE>
