<FIRST>a p BC-Candidates-Press ADV12-2Takes   09-10 0903</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Candidates-Press, ADV 12-2 Takes,0927</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday, Sept 12, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Say They'd Be Accessible Presidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> have issued matching promises of accessibility to the White House press, but neither was saying how often he would hold formal presidential news conferences. The rival presidential nominees made their statements on news and information policies in written responses to inquiries by the <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Managing Editors Association. Their replies were made public as <ORGANIZATION> APME </ORGANIZATION> officers and committee chairmen met in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Monday. `` I hope words like ` accessible,' ` candid,' ` honest' and ` fair' will be adjectives used to describe my relationship with the media by historians,'' Republican <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said `` It certainly is what I will strive for during my tenure as president.'' The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has come under frequent criticism for limiting access to information. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> renewed that criticism. The Democratic nominee prefaced his comments on his plans with a charge that `` the Reagan-Bush administration has waged an assault on the Freedom of Information Act with every weapon in its arsenal.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he has a proven record of accessibility to reporters, and would continue on that course as president. `` Throughout my public career I've believed in a free press and my record shows I've practiced that belief,'' he said. `` As president, I would hope to continue this pattern of accessibility to the White House press corps, giving them and me the opportunity to utilize our First Amendment freedoms. A questionnaire prepared for the FOI committee was given to both candidates. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> responded directly, answering each of the questions. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> replied by issuing a two-part position paper, with one section on the freedom of information law and a second on his press relations. Here is a partial transcript of their replies:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GEORGE BUSH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Q. As president, what sort of tone would you set regarding openness in government, access to government information and freedom of information? A. Within the limits of national security, government should be open to scrutiny by the media and the public. Ours is a democracy where goverment must be accountable to the people. The information-gathering process, from a news conference to the Freedom of Information Act, is vital and essential to our system of democracy. Q. What kind of relationship do you think you've had with the media during your public career? How would you seek to improve it, if at all? A. I think I have had a good relationship with the media. As president, I hope that I will be able to spend more time talking with smaller groups of reporters. I enjoy a good give and take, and that kind of format allows me to get to know reporters a little better and them to know me. Not only will this benefit reporters but, more importantly, such free exchange will ultimately benefit the general public as well. Q. Throughout history, presidents have had a variety of relationships with the media. Are there any styles you would emulate? Are there any you would avoid? When it comes time to write the history of your relations with the media, what will it say? A. With the media, the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> or the public, it would be a mistake to attempt to be something or someone you're not. So, warts and all, what you see is what you'll get. I hope words like `` accessible,'' `` candid,'' `` honest'' and `` fair'' will be adjectives used to describe my relationship with the media by historians. It certainly is what I will strive for during my tenure as president. ... Q. How frequently would you meet with reporters? How would you conduct press conferences? How often would you hold press conferences? Would you make any changes in the way President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has done his press conferences? A. There are a number of ways to communicate with both the media and the public. Press conferences are one important way and they would certainly be central to my effort to ensure accessibility in my administration. One-on-one and group interviews, satellite interviews with regional media, national televised addresses are other examples of methods that a president can and should use to provide the media with opportunities to discuss administration policies and programs. My goal would be to get the right `` mix'' of all of the options available to guarantee an open administration. Realistically, you ca n't put a number on any of the working parts of an open approach to accessibility, but you can make and keep a commitment to the goal itself. Q. More specifically, what message will you send to your executive agencies regarding Freedom of Information requests? A. My message will be simple: obey the law. ... Q. Here's a chance to offer some contructive criticism. What things would you most like to change about the news media? What should the nation's media do differently to better serve the public interest? A. Accuracy and fairness are the name of the game. The media goes to great lengths to be accurate. It needs to go to the same lengths to be fair. While it is often necessary to use unnamed sources in gathering information for a story, it puts the validity of a story at a disadvantage. I hope the news media would rely as little as possible on this approach to information gathering and reporting.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
