<FIRST>a a BC-TickerTalk ADV12   09-10 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, ADV 12,0602</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Sept 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>Analysts See Dividend Growth as a Bright Spot in Dull Market</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investors may be dissatisfied with the progress of stock prices lately, but they should be pleased with rising dividends. That's the case being argued these days by analysts who argue that the `` boring'' stock market of 1988 has actually produced more generous rewards than its notices would suggest. When <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> estimated recently that corporations might increase their dividends by as much as 10 percent this year, little loud cheering was heard on Wall Street. `` Dividends provide half the total return earned by common stocks historically, yet Wall Street traditionally ignores them,'' observed <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuper </PERSON>, executive vice president at the <ORGANIZATION> Centre </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Square </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. `` But watch out, Wall Street. Dividends and, more particularly, dividend growth are likely to take a front seat with investors as the 5 - to 6-percent growth rate of the last five years doubles to 10 - to 12-percent over the next few years It is n't hard to figure out why dividends did n't command as much attention as capital gains when the typical investor thought about the stock market in recent years. If you tried to talk about dividends in the heady 1982-87 bull market, you most likely would have been laughed out of the room. And in the subsequent crash last fall, the furthest thing from anybody's mind was a quarterly dividend check. In any financial season, most professional money managers and brokers are n't paid by their clients to generate dividends. However, analysts who have delved into the subject say that to dismiss dividends as irrelevant misses the point. `` We have always considered yield to be a bedrock indicator of value,'' asserts <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` It is a hard number, unlike earnings or book value, which may exist only in the mind of an accountant. `` Declaring a dividend involves a cash payment. It is not a decision that is taken lightly.'' The dividend bulls base their optimism on several factors, starting with the strong trend in corporate earnings that helps give boards of directors the option of voting dividend increases. Furthermore, says <PERSON> Kuper </PERSON> at Centre Square, companies recently have been paying out less than 40 percent of their earnings as dividends, which is close to a historic low. A normal rate, he says, is more like 50 percent. The Tax Reform Act of 1986, he adds, provided a spur to dividends since it eliminated the special tax treatment of long-term capital gains. That means that dividends now have an equal value with capital gains for taxpaying investors. Based on his estimates for 1989, <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> figures the aggregate yield on the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's composite index of 500 stocks projects to 4.1 percent. `` Contrast that with the mere 2.6 percent available at the market top last year,'' he says. `` These numbers are unlikely to make anyone's adrenaline flow,'' he acknowledges. `` Stocks are bought for appreciation, not yield. `` But we are more interested in value than pizzazz at this stage, and 4.1 percent is a comfortable number.'' For the first two-thirds of 1988, <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> adds, the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P 500 was up about 7 percent. `` Since the yield is about 4 percent, total return is 11 percent. `` This compares well with the 10 percent -LRB- annual -RRB- long-term return on stocks. Boring might not be so bad.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Sept 12</NOTE>
