<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Head Lower</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Concern about the worldwide oil glut continues to weigh heavy on the futures market. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the October contract for delivery of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, fell 30 cents a 42-gallon barrel Friday to $ 14.18. The contract had risen 32 cents on Thursday after falling sharply earlier in the week. Contracts for refined oil products traded on the exchange also declined. Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery plunged 0.93 cent a gallon to 42.06 cents, after rising 0.40 cent the previous session. Analysts attributed the decline to the end of the traditional driving season on Labor Day. The October wholesale heating oil contract, which gained 0.24 cent Thursday, fell 0.90 cent to 40.97 a gallon. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON>, an energy analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said prices started out firm amid speculation that the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>' price monitoring committee might hold an emergency meeting. But with those prospects unconfirmed, prices took a nosedive, he said. `` The sellers came out of the woodwork ...,'' <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON> said. The Saudi Arabian newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Al-Sharq </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bali </ORGANIZATION> quoted unnamed high-level Arab oil sources Friday as saying <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> called for a special meeting later this month of the price-monitoring committee to help stem the decline in oil prices. But the newspaper also said a moderate member of the five-member committee was opposed to the meeting. Crude prices on Tuesday and Wednesday hit their lowest point since Oct. 29, 1986, when they reached $ 13.73 per barrel. The following day the price leaped to $ 15.04 a barrel.
