<FIRST>d f PM-EconomyRdp     09-10 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wholesale Prices Climb, But Markets Unconcerned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The government says wholesale prices rose 0.6 percent in August, but the rise was a slight 0.3 percent excluding food and energy, and traders took the report as good news on inflation. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday the August rise, excluding the volatile food and energy categories, was half the increase of July. Another drop in oil prices also helped the inflation picture. And gold prices plunged and bonds rose, a classic sign that investors were less concerned about inflation. Gold, which investors hold as a hedge against inflation, sank $ 7.25 a troy ounce to $ 421.25 an ounce in late <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trading, its lowest point since early 1987. Bond prices, which are hurt by inflation fears, finished higher after seesawing through a volatile trading session, pushing key interest rates below 9 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s closely watched 30-year bond rose 9-16 point, or about $ 5.60 for every $ 1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves inversely to its price and is often an indicator of interest rate trends, fell to 8.97 percent from 9.03 percent late Thursday. Meanwhile, stock prices took a zigzag path, winding up with a modest gain in continued sluggish trading. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.69 to 2,068.81. Crude oil futures plunged on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> amid rumors <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> had vetoed proposals for a special meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> pricing committee. On other exchanges, contracts for future delivery of precious metals, grains, soybeans, livestock and meat all finished moderately to sharply lower while stock-index futures advanced.
